# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: achaemenid-empire
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] Mohammad Ali Shah Qajar, who had ascended the throne on 3 January 1907, opposed the constitution of 1906 that had been ratified during the reign of his father, Mozaffar ad-Din Shah Qajar.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] After his ascension, the Anglo-Russian Convention in August 1907 divided Iran into a Russian sphere of influence in the North, a British sphere of influence in the South, and a neutral zone in the center.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] The British abandoned the Constitutionalists in favour of the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] The Shah later tried to subdue and eliminate the Majles with military and political support from Russia and Britain.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] During the constitutional revolution, the Shah confined himself to his residence at the Bagh-e Shah fort in the west of Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] He enlisted the help of the Cossack Brigade to control the revolution, leaving the city of Tehran at their mercy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] The loyalty of the Cossack Brigade was fully guaranteed, not only by the previous purge carried out by commander Vladimir Liakhov, but also by the Shah's distribution of a special bonus in 1908.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] Liakhov led the force in shelling the Majles and executing several leaders of the Constitutional Movement on 23 June 1908.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] His forces then plundered the parliament and damaged the building.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] This event led to the beginning of a period known as the "Minor Tyranny".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] Liakhov was subsequently made Military Governor of Tehran by the Shah, transforming the city into a military garrison.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] However, in July 1909, pro-Constitution forces marched from Iran's Azerbaijan province to Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] They were able to capture Tehran, depose the Shah in favour of his son, Ahmad Shah Qajar, and re-establish the constitution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] Colonel Liakhov and his forces served the Shah until July 1909, when the Shah abdicated and fled to Russia, resulting in the surrender of Liakhov and the Persian Cossack Brigade.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1908-bombardment-of-the-majlis] Liakhov was pardoned by the Constitutional leaders probably for the fear of a Russian attack and was sent back to Saint Petersburg, where he would be dismissed soon after to serve in the Caucasus campaign of World War I.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The events began with a coup by the Persian Cossack Brigade headed by Reza Khan on 22 February 1921.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The precise level of British involvement in the coup remains a matter of historical debate, but it is almost certain that Edmund Ironside provided advice to the plotters.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] With this coup Zia ol Din Tabatabaee took over power and became prime minister.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The coup was largely bloodless and faced little resistance.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] With his expanded forces and the Cossack Brigade, Reza Khan launched successful military actions to eliminate separatist and dissident movements in Tabriz, Mashhad and the Jangalis in Gilan.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The campaign against Simko and the Kurds was less successful and lasted well into 1922, though it eventually concluded with Iranian success.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] In late 1920, the Persian Socialist Soviet Republic in Rasht was preparing to march on Tehran with "a guerrilla force of 1,500 Jangalis, Kurds, Armenians and Azerbaijanis", reinforced by the Bolsheviks' Red Army.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] By 1921, Qajar Persia had become corrupt and inefficient.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The oil-rich nation was somewhat reliant on Britain and Russia for military and economic support.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Civil wars earlier in the decade had threatened the government, and the only regular military force at the time was the Cossack Brigade.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Ahmad Shah Qajar, the shah of Iran at the time, had only been crowned in 1909 at the age of eleven and was considered to be a weak, incompetent ruler, especially after British, Russian, and Ottoman occupations of Persia during World War I.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] In 1911, when the capital city, Tehran, had been seized by the Russians, armed Bakhtiari tribesmen, rather than Iranian regular troops, expelled the invaders.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] This further diminished the government's reputation, rendering it almost powerless in time of war.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Britain, which played a major role in Persia, was perturbed by the Qajar government's inability to rule efficiently.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] This inefficiency was the background of a power struggle between Britain and Soviet Russia, each nation hoping to control Persia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] On 14 January 1921, the British General Edmund Ironside chose to promote Reza Khan, who had been leading the Tabriz battalion, to lead the entire brigade.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] About a month later, under British direction, Reza Khan's 3,000-4,000 strong detachment of the Cossack Brigade reached Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] On 18 February 1921, the Cossacks reached Tehran meeting little resistance.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] In the early morning of 21 February, they entered the city.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Only several policemen, taken by surprise, are said to had been killed or wounded in the center of Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Backed by his troops, Reza Khan forced the Cabinet to dissolve and oversaw his own appointment as minister of war.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Reza Khan also ensured that Ahmad, still ruling as shah, appoint Zia ol Din Tabatabaee as prime minister.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] On 26 February, the new government signed a treaty of friendship with the Russian Socialist Federative Soviet Republic, formerly the Russian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] As a result of the treaty, the RSFSR gave up some of its former Russian facilities in Iran, although Soviet diplomats ensured that their nation was allowed to intervene with its military in Iran, as long as the intervention was "self-defense".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The RSFSR also gave up any Russian-owned railroads and ports in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Prior to the coup, Ahmad Qavam, governor of Khorasan, had asserted his loyalty to the Qajar dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] When he refused to recognise the government installed by Reza Khan, he was jailed in Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] During his imprisonment, Qavam cultivated a hatred of the man who had arrested him, Colonel Mohammad Taqi Pessian, now the gendarmerie chief.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Zia ol Din Tabatabaee, who had been installed as prime minister, was removed from office on 25 May by Ahmad Shah's decree.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Shortly thereafter, Qavam was released from prison and given Tabatabaee's former post.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Colonel Pessian refused to accept this betrayal of the coup's ideals of a democratic Iran and began to gather popular support and many tribes flocked to make up his force.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] After Qavam was made prime minister, one of the coup leaders and now the gendarmerie chief Colonel Mohammad Taqi Pessian opposed the new order and erosion of the democratic principles for which he and many of his fellow Iranians had fought and so departed Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Soon at the head of a rebel army, Pessian went to battle with the armies of several regional governors.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] However, the rebels were eventually defeated and Reza Khan ordered that Pessian be beheaded and that the head be returned to Tehran and put on display to prove that Pessian, now a national hero, was dead to quell further rebellions.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The Kurds of Khorasan also revolted in the same year.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The campaign on the Republic of Gilan was taken in early July 1921, by the main Cossack force, led by Vsevolod Starosselsky.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Following a gendarme operation, led by Habibollah Khan (Shiabani), they cleared up Mazandaran and moved into Gilan.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] On 20 August, ahead of the arrival of the Cossacks, the insurgents pulled out of Rasht, retreating towards Enzeli.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The Cossacks entered Rasht on 24 August.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Though further pursuit of the revolutionaries turned successful at Khomam and Pir Bazar, they came under heavy artillery bombardment from the Soviet fleet in the Caspian Sea.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] First, it had been believed that the entire force of 700 men, led by Reza Khan, was annihilated in this event, though later the actual casualty rate was determined to be about 10%, with the rest of them scattering upon the bombardment.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] As a result, Starosselsky ordered an evacuation of Rasht.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The Soviet Republic of Gilan officially came to an end in September 1921.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Mirza and his German friend Gauook (Hooshang) were left alone in the Khalkhal Mountains, and died of frostbite.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] In the aftermath of the 1921 events, relations of the Persian government with the Emirate of Muhammara had also become strained.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] In 1924, the Sheikh Khazal rebellion broke out in Khuzestan, being the first modern Arab nationalist uprising led by the Sheikh of Mohammerah Khaz'al al-Ka'bi.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The rebellion was quickly and effectively suppressed with minimal casualties.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Rezā Khan was placed on the throne by the constitutional assembly in 1925, and many of those involved in the coup were either killed or put in prison.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] Reza Khan was finally declared Shah, taking the surname Pahlavi and thus founding the Pahlavi dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The Pahlavis ruled in Iran until the 1979 Iranian Revolution, when the government was toppled and replaced with that of the Islamic Republic of Iran, headed by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1921-persian-coup-d-état] The day after the Shah left Iran, the revolutionary leaders declared Colonel Mohammad Taghi Pessian the first Martyr of the Revolution, although Pessian was a Secularist.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] In 1949, a **Constituent Assembly** was held in Iran to modify the Persian Constitution of 1906.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi convened the assembly in April; he sought a royal prerogative giving him the right to dismiss the parliament, providing that new elections were held to form a new parliament.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He also specified a method for future amendments to the Constitution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The amendments were made in May 1949 by unanimous vote of the Constituent Assembly.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] During the previous year, the Shah had been considering changes to the Constitution as part of his various plans to increase the power of the monarchy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He was advised against this action by British and American diplomats who thought it unwise to unbalance the separation of powers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] On 4 February 1949, an assassin shot at the Shah, two bullets wounding him.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] That evening, the government declared martial law and a special session of parliament imposed harsh measures against the Shah's political enemies.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The assassin was suspected of being connected to the religious fundamentalist group Fada'iyan-e Islam (Martyrs for Islam, or Devotees of Islam), and loosely associated with the communist-leaning Tudeh Party of Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The parliament outlawed the Tudeh Party and had its leaders arrested.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Shah sent pragmatic Ayatollah Abol-Ghasem Kashani to exile—he had formed a strategic alliance with the Fada'iyan.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] In an atmosphere of national sympathy for the monarchy, the Shah called for a constituent assembly to make amendments to the Constitution, to give him more power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He selected the constituent assembly members from his supporters.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He also increased his pressure for the formation of the Senate of Iran, an upper house of parliament that had been written into the constitution in 1906 but never formed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Senate was expected to favor the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] In 1906 during the drafting of the first Persian Constitution, a bicameral parliament was agreed upon in order to obtain royal approval from Mozaffar ad-Din Shah Qajar.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The shah was to appoint half of the 60 members of the upper house, the Senate.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The other half of the Senate was to be elected by a two-stage process.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The shah expected to be able to control legislation by influencing the Senate.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Mozaffar ad-Din Shah Qajar signed the Constitution at the end of December 1906 but died unexpectedly of a heart attack a few days later.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Radical politicians and other constitutional delegates did not want a Senate, and after the shah died no action was taken to form one.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] In mid-1907, the Anjumans of the Mujahidin, a group of workers, artisans and peasants, called for much wider voting rights for men, and they expressed a wish that the Senate never be formed because it would make the nobility more powerful.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Constitution allowed for a board of ulama (Islamic scholars) who would oversee decisions made by the parliament.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The ulama were to be given veto power over legislation.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Ayatollah Mirza Sayyed Mohammad Tabatabai was one of those who influenced the composition and adoption of the 1906 Constitution, but he never insisted upon the formation of the board of ulama.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Rather, the wishes of the ulama were usually voiced by several members of the Majlis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Ever since assuming the throne in 1941, the young Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi had been working to increase his power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He wanted more weapons and men for the military, which he controlled, and he wanted financial aid from the US.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] In September 1948, he sent National Bank director Abolhassan Ebtehaj to the US to ask the government of Harry S.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Truman for military aid or financial support, and to present the idea that the Shah would activate the Senate.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Ebtehaj disclosed the Shah's wish to change the Constitution so that he could dismiss an uncooperative parliament and authorize new elections.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] This message was affirmed by British Ambassador John Le Rougetel who, seeking stability in Iran's oil industry and continued influence in Iran's parliament, said the UK also advised caution with regard to changes in Iran's constitution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The US State Department prepared a report in January 1949 describing the goal of US diplomacy in Iran as the prevention of any widening of Soviet influence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] To that end, the Shah was seen as the most reliable bulwark against Communist aggression in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He was invited to come visit Truman to discuss mutual concerns.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] On 4 February 1949, the Shah visited the Faculty of Law and Political Science at the University of Tehran, a symbol of secular success against the former monopoly of Islamic scholars who had previously controlled all aspects of the judicial branch of government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Shah's visit was a celebration of the law school's anniversary.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] As the Shah walked from his limousine to the school steps a little after 1 pm, Nasser Fakhrarai approached him from the press area and fired a revolver.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The first shot missed but the Shah's guards dropped and took cover, failing to protect him.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Despite the lack of interference, the second and third shots also missed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The fourth bullet pierced the Shah's lip and cheek, knocking out some front teeth.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] When the gun jammed on the sixth round, Fakhrarai ran to escape.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He was stopped by soldiers who quickly killed him with rifle butts and point-blank shots.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] At 7 pm from the hospital, the Shah spoke by radio to the country, thanking them for their support.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] A photo of him dressed in a hospital gown with his cheek in a bandage was published the next day in the newspapers, showing his stoicism.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] President Truman sent the Shah a note wishing a quick return to good health.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The assassin Fakhrarai was found with a journalist's press card showing that he worked for *Parcham-e Islam* (The Banner of Islam, or Flag of Islam), a religious newspaper opposed to secularism, and that he paid dues to the journalist's labor union loosely associated with the Tudeh Party.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He had been posing as a photographer, hiding the gun in the camera case.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Anxious to blame the Communists, the Shah seized the opportunity to declare a conspiracy of religious and Communist radicals, and he decreed martial law.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He ordered an emergency session of the Majlis the same night he was shot.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Through this session he suppressed his political opposition, including what would prove an ineffective ban on the Tudeh Party.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Shah ordered the closure of newspapers critical of his policies, and for treasonous activities he arrested 28 Tudeh leaders including the most prominent members of the Central Council of United Trade Unions (CCUTU).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Mosaddegh was briefly confined to house arrest, and because the Fada'iyan were suspected, Kashani was exiled to Lebanon.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Later it was determined that Fakhrarai had been planning the assassination alone for three years and had twice attempted it, failing to get close enough each time.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The revolver had been given to him by Abdullah Arghani, a childhood friend who was a more radical member of the Tudeh Party, and was sympathetic to Fakhrarai's assassination plan.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Following the assassination attempt, there was an atmosphere of sympathy expressed by the people of Iran for the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Shah used this to his advantage to promote his goal of increasing the power of the monarchy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] On 17 February 1949, the Majlis passed the Shah's Seven Year Plan, an economic program that had its roots in an economic council of 1946 and a Supreme Planning Board formed in November 1947.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Seven Year Plan was intended to be an autonomous body, independent of political forces, but the Shah saw it as a vehicle for land reform measures that would reinforce his power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] With 25% of its monies earmarked for helping to fight poverty in agrarian Iran, the Shah felt that the Seven Year Plan would make the disaffected rural poor more resistant to Soviet influence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Others thought that so much emphasis on agriculture would prevent Iran from growing out of its traditional role as a resource "appendage" supplying more powerful countries.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Before February 1949, the plan had proven unpopular with the Majlis who saw it as a diminution of their political influence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Despite the Majlis vote of approval, the plan was never to be implemented as intended.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] By May 1949, some 40% had already been dedicated to industrial bailouts as opposed to the 14.3% originally planned.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Another 40% was put toward the completion of rail lines; the Shah's plans were not realized.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] As part of his effort to suppress religious radicals, the Shah asked Ayatollah Seyyed Hossein Borujerdi to rein in the more strident voices among the ulama.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Borujerdi, Iran's senior Islamic scholar, believed in political quietism—that the ulama should not intervene in politics.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Borujerdi had already established a pragmatic realpolitik arrangement with the Shah: the secular political domain would peacefully coexist with the religious domain for the advancement of both.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He called a religious conference to meet in the holy city of Qom beginning 20 February 1949.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Borujerdi directed the 2,000 conference attendees to discuss whether the ulama should take part in political activity; after due consideration, the consensus was for continued quietism.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] (The future Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini was among those who argued unsuccessfully for political activism.) The ulama determined the punishment for violations of quietism would be excommunication.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Even so, some of the more radical ulama stayed active, including the Fada'iyan, and Kashani, exerting his influence from exile.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] On 27 February 1949, the Majlis voted in support of the Shah's bill calling for a Constituent Assembly to re-examine the Constitution of 1906.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] In March, the Shah announced the convocation of this body and he raised the question of whether the Senate should be convened for the first time, as allowed for in 1906.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] To fill the Constituent Assembly, the Shah chose men who were friendly to his wishes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Seyyed Mohammad Sadiq Tabatabai, a veteran ally of the Pahlavi dynasty, was made leader.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] While the men were preparing to meet, the Shah pushed through laws against newspaper criticism of the royal family, and laws which changed crown land holdings from general ownership to ownership under his name alone.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Former Prime Minister Ahmad Qavam, writing from exile in Paris, published an open letter to the Shah which was very critical of any change to the Constitution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Qavam compared the Shah negatively to the hated Mohammad Ali Shah Qajar, Iran's short-lived ruler who fought to reverse the democratic advances allowed by his father in 1906.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Qavam said the current shah would create a political backlash if he tried to take more power—a prediction that later proved correct.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Rather than respond personally, the Shah directed former prime minister Ebrahim Hakimi to publish a severe chastisement of Qavam, accusing him of treasonous collusion with the Soviets during the Iran crisis of 1946.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Shah forbid newspapers in Tehran to print Qavam's first letter and a response; only Hakimi's letter was printed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Shah also took away the honorific title of *hazrat-e ashraf* (his noblest excellency) that he had conferred upon Qavam for the same diplomatic achievements that were now being called treason.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Mosaddegh worked to secure the release of some of those who had been arrested, succeeding to free labor leader Taghi Fadakar.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] He was not successful with others of the labor activists who had been arrested or denounced for treason.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Nineteen of these were sentenced by the Tehran Military Court to various prison terms on 23 April, and eight top leaders were sentenced to death on 18 May *in absentia*, including Communist labor organizer Reza Rousta.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] Seven of the condemned men were from the CCUTU.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Constituent Assembly met for three weeks beginning 21 April 1949.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] A minor change was made to the Constitution regarding the process by which future amendments were to be implemented.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] At the same time, the Majlis passed the Shah's bill to hold elections enabling the Senate to be formed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The Constitution as amended in 1949 remained unchanged until 1957 when the number of Majlis seats was increased by two, and the Shah was given the right to send financial legislation back to the Majlis for reconsideration.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] The 1963 Iranian constitutional referendum, was seen as an approval of the Shah's White Revolution program including women's right to vote and compulsory education of children.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] From 1950 through 1953, Mosaddegh sought to abolish the Senate; it was finally dissolved in early 1979 during the Iranian Revolution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1949-iranian-constituent-assembly-election] A revolutionary Assembly of Experts met in June 1979 to establish an entirely new Constitution for the Islamic Republic of Iran, approved in the December 1979 Iranian constitutional referendum.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] On 19 August 1953, Prime Minister of Iran Mohammad Mosaddegh was overthrown in a coup d'état that strengthened the rule of Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, the Shah of Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In the months preceding the coup, Mosaddegh had consolidated power by orchestrating a referendum to dissolve parliament that was widely described as fraudulent, and he later refused to step down after the Shah attempted to dismiss him as prime minister.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] It was instigated by the United Kingdom (MI6), under the name **Operation Boot** and the United States (CIA), under the name **TP-AJAX Project** or **Operation Ajax**.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] A key motive was to protect British oil interests in Iran after Mosaddegh nationalized the country's oil industry.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh had sought to audit the documents of the Anglo-Iranian Oil Company (AIOC), a British corporation (now part of BP), to verify that AIOC was paying the contracted royalties to Iran, and to limit their control over Iranian oil reserves.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Upon the AIOC's refusal to cooperate with the Iranian government, the parliament (Majlis) voted to nationalize Iran's oil industry and to expel foreign corporate representatives from the country.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] After this vote, Britain instigated a worldwide boycott of Iranian oil to pressure Iran economically.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Initially, Britain mobilized its military to seize control of the British-built Abadan oil refinery, then the world's largest, but Prime Minister Clement Attlee opted instead to tighten the economic boycott while using agents to undermine Mosaddegh's government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Judging Mosaddegh to be unamenable and fearing the growing influence of the communist Tudeh, UK prime minister Winston Churchill decided in early 1953 to solicit the Eisenhower administration and overthrow Iran's government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The preceding Truman administration had opposed a coup, fearing the precedent that Central Intelligence Agency involvement would set, and the U.S. government had been considering unilateral action (without UK support) to assist the Mosaddegh government as late as 1952.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] British intelligence and the UK government's solicitations to the US were instrumental in initiating and planning the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Following the coup, a government under General Fazlollah Zahedi was formed which allowed Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, the shah of Iran (Persian for 'king'), to rule more firmly as monarch.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] He relied heavily on United States support to hold on to power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] According to the CIA's declassified documents and records, some of the most feared mobsters in Tehran were hired by the CIA to stage pro-shah riots on 19 August.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Other men paid by the CIA were brought into Tehran in buses and trucks and took over the streets of the city.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Between 200 and 300 people were killed because of the conflict.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh was arrested, tried and convicted of treason by the Shah's military court.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] On 21 December 1953, he was sentenced to three years in jail, then placed under house arrest for the remainder of his life.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Other Mosaddegh supporters were imprisoned, and several received the death penalty.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The coup strengthened the Shah's authority, and he continued to rule Iran for the next 26 years as a pro-Western monarch until he was overthrown in the Iranian Revolution in 1979.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In August 2013, the U.S. government formally acknowledged the U.S. role in the coup by releasing a bulk of previously classified government documents that show it was in charge of both the planning and the execution of the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] According to American journalist Stephen Kinzer, the operation included false flag attacks, paid protesters, provocations, the bribing of Iranian politicians and high-ranking security and army officials, as well as pro-coup propaganda.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The CIA is quoted as acknowledging the coup was carried out "under CIA direction" and "as an act of U.S. foreign policy, conceived and approved at the highest levels of government".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In 2023, the CIA took credit for the coup, which some scholars had previously disagreed with, while others agreed that the U.S. and Britain had engineered the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Throughout the 19th century, Iran was caught between two advancing imperial powers, Russia and Britain.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In 1892, the British diplomat George Curzon described Iran as "pieces on a chessboard upon which is being played out a game for the dominion of the world." During the latter half of the 19th century, the concession policies of the monarchy faced increased opposition.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] However, the Reuter concession was never put into effect because of violent opposition at home and from Russia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In 1892 the Shah was forced to revoke a tobacco monopoly given to Major G.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Talbot, following protests and a widespread tobacco boycott.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In 1901, Mozzafar al-Din Shah Qajar granted a 60-year petroleum search concession to William Knox D'Arcy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] D'Arcy paid £20,000 (equivalent to £2.8 million in 2024), according to journalist-turned-historian Stephen Kinzer, and promised equal ownership shares, with 16% of any future net profit, as calculated by the company.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Elwell-Sutton wrote, in 1955, that "Persia's share was 'hardly spectacular' and no money changed hands." On 31 July 1907, D'Arcy withdrew from his private holdings in Persia, and transferred them to the British-owned Burmah Oil Company.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] On 26 May 1908, British geologist George Bernard Reynolds struck oil at a depth of 1,180 feet (360 m).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The company grew slowly until World War I, when Persia's strategic importance led the British government to buy a controlling share in the company, essentially nationalizing British oil production in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The British angered the Persians by intervening in their domestic affairs, including in the Persian Constitutional Revolution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Massive popular protests had forced Mozzafar al-Din Shah to allow for the Constitution of 1906, which limited his powers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] It allowed for a parliament elected by the people to make the laws, and a prime minister to sign and carry them out.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The prime minister would be confirmed by the shah after a vote in Parliament.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Nevertheless, the new constitution gave the shah many executive powers as well.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] It allowed for the shah to issue royal decrees (Farman), gave him the power to dismiss prime ministers, appoint half of the members of the Senate (which was not convened until 1949), and introduce bills to dissolve Parliament.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] It abolished arbitrary rule, but the shah served as an executive, rather than in a ceremonial role.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Constitutional Revolution was opposed by the British and Russians, who attempted to subvert it through the backing of Mohammad Ali Shah Qajar (the son of Mozzafar-e-din Shah), who tried to break up the democratic government by force.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] A guerrilla movement led by Sattar Khan deposed him in 1910.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In the aftermath of World War I there was widespread political dissatisfaction with the royalty terms of the British petroleum concession, under the Anglo-Persian Oil Company (APOC), whereby Persia received 16% of "net profits".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In 1921, after years of severe mismanagement under the Qajar dynasty, a coup d'état (allegedly backed by the British) brought a general, Reza Khan, into the government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By 1923, he had become prime minister, and gained a reputation as an effective politician with a lack of corruption.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By 1925 under his influence, Parliament voted to remove Ahmad Shah Qajar from the throne, and Reza Khan was crowned Reza Shah Pahlavi, of the Pahlavi dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Reza Shah began a rapid and successful modernization program in Persia, which up until that point had been considered to be among the most impoverished countries in the world.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Nevertheless, Reza Shah was also a very harsh ruler who did not tolerate dissent.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By the 1930s, he had suppressed all opposition, and had sidelined the democratic aspects of the constitution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Opponents were jailed and in some cases even executed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] While some agreed with his policies, arguing that it was necessary as Iran was in such turmoil, others argued that it was unjustified.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] One such opponent was a politician named Mohammad Mosaddegh, who was jailed in 1940.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The experience gave him a lasting dislike for authoritarian rule and monarchy, and it helped make Mosaddegh a dedicated advocate of complete oil nationalization in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Reza Shah attempted to attenuate the power of the colonial forces in Iran, and was successful to a large extent.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] However, he also needed them to help modernize the country.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] He did so by balancing the influence of various colonial powers, including that of Britain and Germany.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In the 1930s, Reza Shah tried to terminate the APOC concession that the Qajar dynasty had granted, but Iran was still weak and Britain would not allow it.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The concession was renegotiated on terms again favorable to the British (although the D'Arcy Concession was softened).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] On 21 March 1935, Reza Shah changed the name of the country from Persia to Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Anglo-Persian Oil Company was then renamed the Anglo-Iranian Oil Company (AIOC).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In 1941, after the German invasion of the Soviet Union, British and Soviet forces invaded and occupied Iran, which was largely unopposed by the Iranian government and military.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] After World War II had broken out, Reza Shah had declared Iran's neutrality, and attempted to appease the British, Soviets and Germans, all of whom maintained a degree of influence in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The primary reasons behind the Anglo-Soviet invasion was to remove German influence in Iran and secure control over Iran's oil fields and the Trans-Iranian Railway in order to deliver supplies to the USSR.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Reza Shah was deposed and exiled by the British to South Africa, and his 22-year-old son Mohammad Reza Pahlavi was installed as the new Shah of Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mohammad Reza Pahlavi was supported by the Allies because they viewed him as being less able to act against their interests in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The new Shah, unlike his father, was initially a mild leader and at times indecisive.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] During the 1940s he did not for most part take an independent role in the government, and much of Reza Shah's authoritarian policies were rolled back.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Iranian democracy effectively was restored during this period as a result.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The British occupation force withdrew from Iran after the end of the war.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] However, under Stalin, the Soviet Union partly remained by sponsoring two *People's Democratic Republics* within Iran's borders.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The related conflict was ended when the US lobbied for the Iranian Army to reassert control over the two occupied territories.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The earlier agreed-upon Soviet–Iranian oil agreement would never be honored.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Nationalist leaders in Iran became influential by looking for a reduction in long-term foreign interventions in their country—especially the oil concession which was very profitable for the West and not very profitable for Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] U.S. objectives in the Middle East remained the same between 1947 and 1952 but its strategy changed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Washington remained "publicly in solidarity and privately at odds" with Britain, its World War II ally.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Britain's empire was steadily weakening, and with an eye on international crises, the U.S. re-appraised its interests and the risks of being identified with British colonial interests.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Iran's oil had been discovered and later controlled by the British-owned AIOC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Popular discontent with the AIOC began in the late 1940s: a large segment of Iran's public and a number of politicians saw the company as exploitative and a central tool of continued British imperialism in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In 1949, an assassin attempted to kill the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Shocked by the experience and emboldened by public sympathy for his injury, the Shah began to take an increasingly active role in politics.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] He quickly organized the Iran Constituent Assembly to amend the constitution to increase his powers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] He established the Senate of Iran, which had been a part of the Constitution of 1906 but had never been convened.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Shah had the right to appoint half the senators, and he chose men sympathetic to his aims.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh thought this increase in the Shah's political power was not democratic; he believed that the Shah should "reign, but not rule" in a manner similar to Europe's constitutional monarchies.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Led by Mosaddegh, political parties and opponents of the Shah's policies banded together to form a coalition known as the National Front.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Oil nationalization was a major policy goal for the coalition.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By 1951, the National Front had won majority seats for the popularly elected Majlis (Parliament of Iran).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] According to Iran's constitution, the majority elected party in the parliament would choose its prime minister candidate by vote, after which the Shah would confirm the candidate to power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Prime Minister Haj Ali Razmara, who opposed the oil nationalization, was assassinated by the hardline Fadaiyan e-Islam (whose spiritual leader was the Ayatollah Abol-Qassem Kashani, a mentor to the future Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini,).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] After the National Front dominated the voting in Parliament, Mosaddegh was confirmed prime minister of Iran by the Shah (replacing Hossein Ala, who had replaced Razmara).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Under heavy pressure by the National Front, the assassin of Razmara (Khalil Tahmasebi) was released and pardoned.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] For the time being, Mosaddegh and Kashani were allies of convenience, as Mosaddegh saw that Kashani could mobilize the "religious masses", while Kashani wanted Mosaddegh to drive out British and other foreign influence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Kashani's Fadaiyan mobs often violently attacked the opponents of nationalization and opponents of the National Front government, as well as "immoral objects", acting at times as unofficial "enforcers" for the movement.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] However, by late 1952 Mosaddegh was becoming increasingly opposed to Kashani, as the latter was contributing to mass political instability in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Kashani in turn, berated Mosaddegh for not "Islamizing" Iran, as he (Mosaddegh) was a firm believer in the separation of religion and state.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Shah and his new prime minister Mosaddegh had an antagonistic relationship.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Part of the problem stemmed from the fact that Mosaddegh was connected by blood to the former royal Qajar dynasty, and saw the Pahlavi king as a usurper to the throne.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] But the real issue stemmed from the fact that Mosaddegh represented a pro-democratic force that wanted to temper the Shah's rule in Iranian politics.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] He wanted the Shah to be a ceremonial monarch rather than a ruling monarch, thus giving the elected government power instead of the un-elected Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] While the constitution of Iran gave the Shah the power to rule directly, Mosaddegh used the united National Front bloc and the widespread popular support for the oil nationalization vote (the latter which the Shah supported as well) in order to block the Shah's ability to act.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] As a result, the oil nationalization issue became increasingly intertwined with Mosaddegh's pro-democracy movement.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The dejected Shah was angered by Mosaddegh's "insolence" (according to Abbas Milani, he angrily paced in the rooms of his palace at the thought that he would be reduced to a figurehead).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] But Mosaddegh and the oil nationalization's popularity prevented the Shah from acting against his prime minister (which was allowed under Iran's constitution), something that Mosaddegh felt a king had no right to do.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In 1952 the Shah dismissed Mosaddegh, replacing him with Ahmad Qavam (a veteran prime minister).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] But widespread protests by Mosaddegh supporters resulted in the Shah immediately reinstating him.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In late 1951, Iran's Parliament in a near unanimous vote approved the oil nationalization agreement.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The bill was widely popular among most Iranians, and generated a huge wave of nationalism, and immediately put Iran at loggerheads with Britain (the handful of MPs that disagreed with it voted for it as well in the face of overwhelming popular support, and the Fadaiyan's wrath).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The nationalization made Mosaddegh instantly popular among millions of Iranians, cementing him as a national hero, and placing him and Iran at the center of worldwide attention.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Britain now faced the newly elected nationalist government in Iran where Mosaddegh, with strong backing of the Iranian parliament and people, demanded more favorable concessionary arrangements, which Britain vigorously opposed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mohammad Mosaddegh attempted to negotiate with the AIOC, but the company rejected his proposed compromise.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh's plan, based on the 1948 compromise between the Venezuelan Government of Rómulo Gallegos and Creole Petroleum, would divide the profits from oil 50/50 between Iran and Britain.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Against the recommendation of the United States, Britain refused this proposal and began planning to undermine and overthrow the Iranian government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In July 1951, the American diplomat Averell Harriman went to Iran to negotiate an Anglo-Iranian compromise, asking the Shah's help; his reply was that "in the face of public opinion, there was no way he could say a word against nationalisation".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Harriman held a press conference in Tehran, calling for reason and enthusiasm in confronting the "nationalisation crisis".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] As soon as he spoke, a journalist rose and shouted: "We and the Iranian people all support Premier Mosaddegh and oil nationalisation!" Everyone present began cheering and then marched out of the room; the abandoned Harriman shook his head in dismay.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] On a visit to the United States in October 1951, Mosaddegh—in spite of the popularity of nationalization in Iran—agreed in talks with George C.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] McGhee to a complex settlement of the crisis involving the sale of the Abadan Refinery to a non-British company and Iranian control of the extraction of crude oil.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The US waited until Winston Churchill became prime minister to present the deal, believing he would be more flexible, but the deal was rejected by the British.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By September 1951, the British had virtually ceased Abadan oil field production, forbidden British export to Iran of key British commodities (including sugar and steel), and had frozen Iran's hard currency accounts in British banks.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] British Prime Minister Clement Attlee considered seizing the Abadan Oil Refinery by force, but instead settled on an embargo by the Royal Navy, stopping any ship transporting Iranian oil for carrying so-called "stolen property".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] On his re-election as prime minister, Winston Churchill took an even harder stance against Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The United Kingdom took its anti-nationalization case against Iran to the International Court of Justice at The Hague; PM Mosaddegh said the world would learn of a "cruel and imperialistic country" stealing from a "needy and naked people".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The court ruled that it had no jurisdiction over the case.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Nevertheless, the British continued to enforce the embargo of Iranian oil.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In August 1952, Iranian Prime Minister Mosaddegh invited an American oil executive to visit Iran and the Truman administration welcomed the invitation.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] However, the suggestion upset Churchill, who insisted that the U.S. not undermine his campaign to isolate Mosaddegh because of British support for the U.S. in the Korean War.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] In mid-1952, Britain's embargo of Iranian oil was devastatingly effective.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] British agents in Tehran "worked to subvert" the government of Mosaddegh, who sought help from President Truman and then the World Bank but to no avail.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] "Iranians were becoming poorer and unhappier by the day" and Mosaddegh's political coalition was fraying.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] To make matters worse, the Speaker of the Parliament Ayatollah Kashani, Mosaddegh's main clerical supporter, became increasingly opposed to the Prime Minister, because Mosaddegh was squeezing him out of power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By 1953, he had completely turned on him, and supported the coup, depriving Mosaddegh of religious support, while giving it to the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] He was joined in this by a young and relatively unknown mullah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iran's future revolutionary supreme leader who also condemned the Mossadegh government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] While the National Front, which often supported Mosaddegh, won handily in the big cities, there was no one to monitor voting in the rural areas.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Violence broke out in Abadan and other parts of the country where elections were hotly contested.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] To make matters worse, the Communist Tudeh Party, which supported the Soviet Union and had attempted to kill the Shah only four years earlier, began to infiltrate the military and send mobs to "support Mosaddegh" (but in reality to marginalize all non-Communist opponents).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Earlier, the Tudeh had denounced Mosaddegh, but by 1953 they changed tack and decided to "support" him.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] However, by 1953 he and the Tudeh had formed an unofficial alliance of convenience with each other; the Tudeh were the "foot soldiers" for his government, effectively replacing the Fadaiyan in that role, all the while secretly hoping that Mosaddegh would institute communism.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Worried about Britain's other interests in Iran, and thanks to the Tudeh Party, believing that Iran's nationalism was really a Soviet-backed plot, Britain persuaded US Secretary of State John Foster Dulles that Iran was falling to the Soviets—effectively exploiting the American Cold War mindset.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Truman was busy fighting a war in Korea, he did not agree to overthrow the government of Prime Minister Mohammad Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Eisenhower became president, the UK convinced the U.S. to undertake a joint coup d'état.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By 1953, economic tensions caused by the British embargo and political turmoil began to take a major toll on Mosaddegh's popularity and political power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] He was increasingly blamed for the economic and political crisis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Political violence was becoming widespread in the form of street clashes between rival political groups.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh was losing popularity and support among the working class which had been his strongest supporters.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] As he lost support, he became more autocratic.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] As early as August 1952, he began to rely on emergency powers to rule, generating controversy among his supporters.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] After an assassination attempt upon one of his cabinet ministers and himself, he ordered the jailing of dozens of his political opponents.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] This act created widespread anger among the general public, and led to accusations that Mosaddegh was becoming a dictator.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Tudeh Party's unofficial alliance with Mosaddegh led to fears of communism, and increasingly it was the communists who were taking part in pro-Mosaddegh rallies and attacking opponents.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By mid-1953 a mass of resignations by Mosaddegh's parliamentary supporters reduced the National Front seats in Parliament.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] A referendum to dissolve parliament and give the prime minister power to make law was submitted to voters, and it passed with 99.9 percent approval, 2,043,300 votes to 1300 votes against.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The referendum was widely seen by opponents as treason and an act against the Shah, who was stripped of military power and control over national resources.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] This act would be one of many key factors in a chain of events leading to Mosaddegh's deposition.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Shah himself initially opposed the coup plans and supported the oil nationalization, but he joined in after being informed by the CIA that he too would be "deposed" if he didn't play along.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The experience left him with a lifelong awe of American power and would contribute to his pro-US policies while generating a hatred of the British.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh's decision to dissolve Parliament also contributed to his decision.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The official pretext for the start of the coup was Mosaddegh's decree to dissolve Parliament, giving himself and his cabinet complete power to rule, while effectively stripping the Shah of his powers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] It resulted in him being accused of giving himself "total and dictatorial powers." The Shah, who had been resisting the CIA's demands for the coup, finally agreed to support it.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Having obtained the Shah's concurrence, the CIA executed the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Firmans (royal decrees) dismissing Mosaddegh and appointing General Fazlollah Zahedi (a loyalist who had helped Reza Shah reunify Iran decades earlier) were drawn up by the coup plotters and signed by the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Having signed the decrees and delivered them to General Zahedi, he and Queen Soraya departed for a week-long vacation in northern Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh had been warned of the plans to overthrow his government by the Tudeh Party, whose cells had infiltrated the military, and as such, Mossadegh was able to avoid arrest.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] On Sunday 16 August, Colonel Nematollah Nassiri, delivered to Mosaddegh the firman from the Shah dismissing him, but Mossadegh rejected the firman and had Nassiri arrested.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Henderson on 18 August, Mossadegh argued that regardless of the authenticity of any firman dismissing him, he would ignore it, as in his view, the Shah had no authority to dismiss him as a purely constitutional monarch.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh's supporters took to the streets in violent protests.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Following the failed coup attempt, the Shah, accompanied by his second wife Soraya Esfandiary-Bakhtiari and Aboul Fath Atabay fled to Baghdad.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Arriving unannounced, the Shah asked for permission for himself and his consort to stay in Baghdad for a few days before continuing on to Europe.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] After high-level Government consultations, they were escorted to the White House, the Iraqi Government's guest house, before flying to Italy in a plane flown by Mohammad Amir Khatami.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] After the first coup attempt failed, General Zahedi, along with his son, Ardeshir Zahedi, Gilanshah, and the Rashidiyan brothers, all took refuge in the safe custody of a CIA station in Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh ordered security forces to capture the coup plotters, and dozens were imprisoned.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Believing that he had succeeded, and that he was in full control of the government, Mosaddegh erred.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Assuming that the coup had failed, he asked his supporters to return to their homes and to continue with their lives as normal.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Tudeh party members also returned to their homes, no longer carrying out enforcement duties.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The CIA was ordered to leave Iran, although Kermit Roosevelt Jr. was slow to receive the message—allegedly due to MI6 interference—and eagerly continued to foment anti-Mosaddegh unrest.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] General Zahedi, who was still on the run, secretly met with the pro-Shah Ayatollah Mohammad Behbahani and other Shah supporters.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Backed by CIA money (derisively known as "Behbahani dollars"), they developed a strategy to stoke class and religious resentment toward the Mosaddegh government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Shah's flight from Iran, Mosaddegh's arrests of political opponents, and fears of communism had already soured many upper-class Iranians on the prime minister.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The plotters sought to capitalize on these anxieties.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Ayatollah Behbahani also used his influence to rally religious demonstrators against Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] On 19 August, Mosaddegh issued a decree banning all demonstrations on that day.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] However, mobilization of crowds and street protests widely believed to have been organized with CIA assistance, had occurred to create the impression of popular unrest and opposition to Mosaddegh's government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Bloody street battles were observed to have broken out in Tehran between Tudeh Party activists and right wing parties, whose offices were attacked by the communists.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] At the same time pro-Shah crowds began gathering in the streets.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By the middle of the day, large crowds of regular citizens, armed with improvised weapons, took to the streets in mass demonstrations, and beat back the Tudeh Party members.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Under Zahedi's authority, the army left its barracks and drove off the communist Tudeh and then stormed all government buildings with the support of demonstrators.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh fled after a tank fired a single shell into his house, but he later turned himself in to the army's custody.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] To prevent further bloodshed, he refused a last attempt to organize his supporters.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] By the end of the day, Zahedi and the army were in control of the government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] According to Hugh Wilford in his book published in 2013, despite the CIA's role in creating the conditions for the coup, there was little evidence to prove that Kermit Roosevelt Jr. or other CIA officials were directly responsible for the actions of the demonstrators or the army on 19 August.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Meanwhile, in 2017, the CIA released documents revealing that the networks established by British intelligence services had been used to run a campaign of propaganda and paid-for protests, resulting in the rapid destabilization of the nation.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Gasiorowski wrote in 2019, Ray Takeyh's view would be based on a "deeply flawed and highly selective reading" of the available evidence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] The Shah stayed in a hotel in Italy until he learned what had transpired, upon which he "chokingly declared": "I knew they loved me." Allen Dulles, the director of the CIA, flew back with the Shah from Rome to Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] Mosaddegh was arrested, tried, and originally sentenced to death.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p01] But on the Shah's personal orders, his sentence was commuted to three years' solitary confinement in a military prison, followed by house arrest until his death.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] As a condition for restoring the Anglo-Iranian Oil Company, in 1954 the US required removal of the AIOC's monopoly; five American petroleum companies, Royal Dutch Shell, and the Compagnie Française des Pétroles were to draw Iran's petroleum after the successful coup d'état—Operation Ajax.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Shah declared this to be a "victory" for Iranians, with the massive influx of money from this agreement resolving the economic collapse from the last three years, and allowing him to carry out his planned modernization projects.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] As part of that, the CIA organized anti-Communist guerrillas to fight the Tudeh Party if they seized power in the chaos of Operation Ajax.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Released National Security Archive documents showed that Undersecretary of State Walter Bedell Smith reported that the CIA had agreed with Qashqai tribal leaders, in south Iran, to establish a clandestine safe haven from which U.S.-funded guerrillas and spies could operate.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The CIA sent Major General Norman Schwarzkopf Sr. to persuade the exiled Shah to return to rule Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Schwarzkopf trained the security forces that would become known as SAVAK to secure the shah's hold on power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] According to a heavily redacted CIA document released to the National Security Archive in response to a Freedom of Information request, "Available documents do not indicate who authorized CIA to begin planning the operation, but it almost certainly was President Eisenhower himself.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] One version of the CIA history, written by Wilber, referred to the operation as TPAJAX.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] A tactic Roosevelt admitted to using was bribing demonstrators into attacking symbols of the Shah, while chanting pro-Mosaddegh slogans.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] As king, the Shah was largely seen as a symbol of Iran at the time by many Iranians and monarchists.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Roosevelt declared that the more that these agents showed their hate for the Shah and attacked his symbols, the more it caused the average Iranian citizen to dislike and distrust Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The British and American spy agencies strengthened the monarchy in Iran by backing the pro-western Shah for the next 26 years.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Some Iranian clerics cooperated with the western spy agencies because they were dissatisfied with Mosaddegh's secular government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] While the broad outlines of the operation are known, "...the C.I.A.'s records were widely thought by historians to have the potential to add depth and clarity to a famous but little-documented intelligence operation", reporter Tim Weiner wrote in *The New York Times* 29 May 1997.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Donald Wilber, one of the CIA officers who planned the 1953 coup in Iran, wrote an account titled, *Clandestine Service History Overthrow of Premier Mossadeq of Iran: November 1952 – August 1953*.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Wilber said one goal of the coup was to strengthen the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The National Security Archive at George Washington University contains the full account by Wilber, along with many other coup-related documents and analysis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In August 2013, on the 60th anniversary of the coup, the US government released documents showing they were involved in staging the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The documents also describe the motivations behind the coup and the strategies used to stage it.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The UK had sought to censor information regarding its role in the coup; a significant number of documents about the coup remained classified.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The release of the declassified documents, which marked the first US official acknowledgement of its role, was seen as a goodwill gesture on the part of the Obama administration.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] According to Aljazeera, the deputy director of the National Security Archive, Malcolm Byrne, disclosed that the CIA documented the secret histories purposely for official use.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Public awareness of American and British participation in Mosaddeq's overthrow was long-standing.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] An internal narrative from the middle of the 1970s called "The Battle for Iran" makes a clear reference to the CIA's involvement.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In 1981, the agency made a highly edited version of the report public in reaction to an ACLU lawsuit, but it blocked out all mentions of TPAJAX, the code name for the American-led operation.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] These references can be found in the most recent release in 2013, which is thought to be the CIA's first official admission that the agency assisted in the coup's planning and execution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In June 2017, the United States State Department's Office of the Historian released its revised historical account of the event.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The volume of historical records "focuses on the evolution of U.S. thinking on Iran as well as the U.S.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Government covert operation that resulted in Mosadeq's overthrow on 19 August 1953".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Though some of the relevant records were destroyed long ago, the release contains a collection of roughly 1,000 pages, only a small number of which remain classified.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] One revelation is that the CIA "attempted to call off the failing coup but was salvaged by an insubordinate spy." The reports released by the U.S. had reached 1,007 pages, consisting of diplomatic cables and letters according to VOA News.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In March 2018, the National Security Archive released a declassified British memo alleging that the United States Embassy sent "large sums of money" to "influential people"—namely senior Iranian clerics—in the days leading up to Mosaddeq's overthrow.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] According to the Guardian, despite the U.S. showing regrets about the coup, it has failed to officially issue an apology over its involvement.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The CIA paid a large sum to carry out the operation.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Depending on the expenses to be counted, the final cost is estimated to vary from $100,000 to $20 million.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] CIA gave Zahedi's government $5 million after the coup,with Zahedi himself receiving an extra million.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Historians disagree on what motivated the United States to change its policy towards Iran and stage the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Middle East historian Ervand Abrahamian identified the coup d'état as "a classic case of nationalism clashing with imperialism in the Third World".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Abrahamian states that Iran's oil was the central focus of the coup, for both the British and the Americans, though "much of the discourse at the time linked it to the Cold War".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Abrahamian said that Mosaddegh "wanted real nationalization, both in theory and practice".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] "The landlords and oil producers had new backing, moreover, as American interests were for the first time exerted in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Cold War was starting, and Soviet challenges were seen in every leftist movement.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] But the reformers were at root nationalists, not communists, and the issue that galvanized them above all others was the control of oil." The belief that oil was the central motivator behind the coup has been echoed in the popular media by authors such as Robert Byrd, Alan Greenspan, and Ted Koppel.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Cold War was at its height in the early 1950s, and the Soviet Union was viewed as an expansionist power seeking world domination.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] A 2019 study by Gasiorowski concluded "that U.S. policymakers did not have compelling evidence that the threat of a Communist takeover was increasing substantially in the months before the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Gasiorowski further states "the major U.S. oil companies were not interested in Iran at this time.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The U.S. majors had increased their production in Saudi Arabia and Kuwait in 1951 in order to make up for the loss of Iranian production; operating in Iran would force them to cut back production in these countries which would create tensions with Saudi and Kuwaiti leaders.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Furthermore, if nationalist sentiments remained high in Iran, production there would be risky.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] U.S. oil companies had shown no interest in Iran in 1951 and 1952.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] By late 1952, the Truman administration had come to believe that participation by U.S. companies in the production of Iranian oil was essential to maintain stability in Iran and keep Iran out of Soviet hands.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In order to gain the participation of the major U.S. oil companies, Truman offered to scale back a large anti-trust case then being brought against them.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Eisenhower administration shared Truman's views on the participation of U.S. companies in Iran and also agreed to scale back the anti-trust case.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] "Britain was the closest ally of the United States, and the two countries were working as partners on a wide range of vitally important matters throughout the world at this time.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Preserving this close relationship was more important to U.S. officials than saving Mosaddeq's tottering regime." A year earlier, British Prime Minister Winston Churchill used Britain's support for the U.S. in the Cold War to insist the United States not undermine his campaign to isolate Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] According to Kinzer, for most Americans, the crisis in Iran became just part of the conflict between Communism and "the Free world".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] "A great sense of fear, particularly the fear of encirclement, shaped American consciousness during this period. ...
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Soviet power had already subdued Latvia, Lithuania, and Estonia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Communist governments were imposed on Bulgaria and Romania in 1946, Hungary and Poland in 1947, and Czechoslovakia in 1948.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Albania and Yugoslavia also turned to communism.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Greek communists made a violent bid for power.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Soviet soldiers blocked land routes to Berlin for sixteen months.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In 1949, the Soviet Union successfully tested a nuclear weapon.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] That same year, pro-Western forces in China lost their Civil War to communists led by Mao Zedong.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] On 11 May 1951, prior to the overthrow of Mosaddegh, Adolf A.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The documentary *Cinematograph* aired on 18 August 2011 on the anniversary of the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In it, BBC admitted for the first time to the role of BBC Persian radio as the propaganda arm of the British government in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The BBC was at times even used directly in the operations, sending coded messages to the coup plotters by changing the wording of its broadcasts.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The National Security Archive released two declassified documents in August 2017 which confirm the British solicitation of the United States' assistance in ousting Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] At the time, the American government was already preparing to aid Mosaddegh in his oil dealings with the British, and believed him to be anti-communist—considerations which made the U.S. government skeptical of the plot.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Since President Truman's term was drawing to a close in January 1953, and there was too much uncertainty and danger associated with the plot, the U.S. government decided not to take action against Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] According to the 1952 documents, it was Christopher Steel, the No 2 official in the British embassy in Washington, who "pitched" the idea of the coup to US officials amid the US-Britain talks which had begun in October.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The document also says that the British officials rejected Paul Nitze's suggestion that, instead of executing a coup, they mount a "campaign" against Ayatollah Abolqasem Kashani, "a leading opponent of British involvement in Iran's oil industry", and the communist Tudeh Party.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] They "pressed the US for a decision" since they knew "the Truman administration was in its final weeks".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] According to Wilber, the British Secret Intelligence Service launched a propaganda campaign via "the press, handbills and the Tehran clergy" to "weaken the Mossadeq government in any way possible".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In the lead-up to the 70th anniversary of the coup in August 2023, David Owen, who was the UK Foreign Secretary in the late 1970s, said that MI6 should follow the example of the CIA and acknowledge its role in the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Mosaddegh appointed a series of secular ministers to his cabinet during his premiership, losing his support with the clergy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In 1953, Ayatollah Abol-Qasem Kashani and his followers organised a series of protests against Mosaddegh's liberal reforms.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] By July 1953 when Mosaddegh asked for a critical extension of his emergency powers, "...
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Clerical members of the Majlis who supported Kashani left the National Front Coalition and set up their own Islamic Faction...".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] This faction then boycotted the 1953 referendum about the dissolution of parliament.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] At 8am on 18 August Ayatollah Behbahani mobilised 3000 stick and club wielding anti-shah protestors formed a mob in Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] This was done in the hope that the removal of Mosaddegh would create a more religious government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Separate mobilisation was instigated by Ayatollah Kashani in the country at this time.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] There has been documentation that both Ayatollah Behbahani and Kashani received funds from the CIA by some sources.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The former's mob would lead Mosaddegh to abandon his residence, and ultimately his capture.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Iranian Historian Michael Axworthy stated that "... [The clergy's] move to oppose Mossadeq was the decisive factor in his downfall...".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The authoritarian monarch appreciated the coup, Kermit Roosevelt wrote in his account of the affair.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] "'I owe my throne to God, my people, my army and to you!' By 'you' he [the shah] meant me and the two countries—Great Britain and the United States—I was representing.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] On 16 June 2000, *The New York Times* published the secret CIA report, "Clandestine Service History, Overthrow of Premier Mossadeq of Iran, November 1952 – August 1953", partly explaining the coup from CIA agent Wilber's perspective.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In a related story, *The New York Times* reporter James Risen penned a story revealing that Wilber's report, hidden for nearly five decades, had recently come to light.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In a review of Tim Weiner's *Legacy of Ashes*, historian Michael Beschloss wrote, "Mr.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Weiner argues that a bad C.I.A. track record has encouraged many of our gravest contemporary problems...
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] A generation of Iranians grew up knowing that the C.I.A. had installed the shah", Mr.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Eisenhower considered the coup a success, but, given its blowback, that opinion is no longer generally held, because of its "haunting and terrible legacy".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Secretary of State, said that intervention by the U.S. in the internal affairs of Iran was a setback for democratic government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The coup is widely believed to have significantly contributed to the 1979 Iranian Revolution, which deposed the "pro-Western" Shah and replaced the monarchy with an "anti-Western" Islamic republic.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] United States Supreme Court Justice William O.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Douglas, who visited Iran both before and after the coup, wrote that "When Mosaddegh and Persia started basic reforms, we became alarmed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] When the Shah returned to Iran after the coup, he was greeted by a cheering crowd.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] He wrote in his memoirs that while he had been a king for over a decade, for the first time he felt that the people had "elected" and "approved" of him, and that he had a "legitimate" popular mandate to carry out his reforms (although some in the crowd may have been bribed).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Shah was never able to remove the reputation of being a "foreign imposed" ruler among non-royalist Iranians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Shah throughout his rule continued to assume that he was supported by virtually everybody in Iran, and sank into deep dejection when in 1978 massive mobs demanded his ouster.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] An immediate consequence of the coup d'état was the Shah's suppression of all republicanist political dissent, especially the liberal and nationalist opposition umbrella group National Front as well as the communist Tudeh Party, and concentration of political power in the Shah and his courtiers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The minister of Foreign Affairs and the closest associate of Mosaddegh, Hossein Fatemi, was executed by order of the Shah's military court by firing squad on 10 November 1954.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] According to Kinzer, "The triumphant Shah [Pahlavi] ordered the execution of several dozen military officers and student leaders who had been closely associated with Mohammad Mosaddegh".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] As part of the post-coup d'état political repression between 1953 and 1958, the Shah outlawed the National Front, and arrested most of its leaders.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Shah personally spared Mosaddegh the death penalty, and he was given 3 years in prison, followed by house arrest for life.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Many supporters of Iran continued to fight against the new regime, yet they were suppressed with some even being killed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The political party that Mosaddegh founded, the National Front of Iran, was later reorganized by Karim Sanjabi, and was later led by the National Poet of Iran Adib Boroumand, who was a strong Mosaddegh supporter and helped spread pro-Mosaddegh propaganda during the Abadan Crisis and its aftermath.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Communist Tudeh bore the main brunt of the crackdown.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Shah's security forces arrested 4,121 Tudeh political activists including 386 civil servants, 201 college students, 165 teachers, 125 skilled workers, 80 textile workers, and 60 cobblers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Forty were executed (primarily for murder, such as Khosrow Roozbeh), another 14 died under torture and over 200 were sentenced to life imprisonment.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Shah's post-coup dragnet also captured 477 Tudeh members ("22 colonels, 69 majors, 100 captains, 193 lieutenants, 19 noncommissioned officers, and 63 military cadets") who were in the Iranian armed forces.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] After their presence was revealed, some National Front supporters complained that this Communist Tudeh military network could have saved Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] However, few Tudeh officers commanded powerful field units, especially tank divisions that might have countered the coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Most of the captured Tudeh officers came from the military academies, police and medical corps.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] At least eleven of the captured army officers were tortured to death between 1953 and 1958.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] After the 1953 coup, the Shah's government formed the SAVAK (secret police), many of whose agents were trained in the United States.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The SAVAK monitored dissidents and carried out censorship.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] After the 1971 Siahkal Incident, it was given a "loose leash" to torture suspected dissidents with "brute force" that, over the years, "increased dramatically", and nearly 100 people were executed for political reasons during the last 20 years of the Shah's rule.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Another effect was sharp improvement of Iran's economy; the British-led oil embargo against Iran ended, and oil revenue increased significantly beyond the pre-nationalisation level.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Shah's government attempted to solve the issue of oil nationalization through this method, and Iran began to develop rapidly under his rule.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Shah later in his memoirs declared that Mosaddegh was a "dictator" who was "damaging" Iran through his "stubbornness", while he (the Shah) "followed" the smarter option.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] By the 1970s, Iran was wealthier than all of its surrounding neighbors, and economists frequently predicted that it would become a major global economic power, and a developed country.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] When the Shah attempted during the 1970s to once again control the oil prices (through OPEC), and cancel the same oil consortium agreement that caused the 1953 coup, it resulted in a massive decline in US support for the Shah, and ironically, hastened his downfall.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] CIA staff historian David Robarge stated: "The CIA carried out [a] successful regime change operation.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] It also transformed a turbulent constitutional monarchy into an absolutist kingship and induced a succession of unintended consequences." The 1979 Iranian Revolution was a most impactful unintended consequence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Kinzer wrote that the 1953 coup d'état was the first time the United States used the CIA to overthrow a "democratically elected", "civil government".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The Eisenhower administration viewed Operation Ajax as a success, with "immediate and far-reaching effect.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] A pro-American government in Iran extended the United States' geographic and strategic advantage in the Middle East, as Turkey, also bordering the USSR, was part of NATO.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In the Islamic Republic, remembrance of the coup is quite different from that of history books published in the West, and follows the precepts of Ayatollah Khomeini that Islamic jurists must guide the country to prevent "the influence of foreign powers".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Men associated with Mosaddegh and his ideals dominated Iran's first post-revolutionary government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] The first prime minister after the Iranian revolution was Mehdi Bazargan, a close associate of Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] But with the subsequent rift between the conservative Islamic establishment and the secular liberal forces, Mosaddegh's work and legacy has been largely ignored by the Islamic Republic establishment.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] However, Mosaddegh remains a popular historical figure among Iranian opposition factions.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Mosaddegh's image is one of the symbols of Iran's opposition movement, also known as the Green Movement.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Kinzer writes that Mosaddegh "for most Iranians" is "the most vivid symbol of Iran's long struggle for democracy" and that modern protesters carrying a picture of Mosaddegh is the equivalent of saying "We want democracy" and "No foreign intervention".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] In the Islamic Republic of Iran, Kinzer's book *All the Shah's Men: An American Coup and the Roots of Middle East Terror* has been censored of descriptions of Ayatollah Abol-Ghasem Kashani's activities during the Anglo-American coup d'état.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] This allegation also is posited in the book *Khaterat-e Arteshbod-e Baznesheshteh Hossein Fardoust* (The Memoirs of Retired General Hossein Fardoust), published in the Islamic Republic and allegedly written by Hossein Fardoust, a former SAVAK officer.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] It says that rather than being a mortal enemy of the British, Mohammad Mosaddegh always favored them, and his nationalisation campaign of the Anglo-Iranian Oil Company was inspired by "the British themselves".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Scholar Ervand Abrahamian suggests that the fact that Fardoust's death was announced before publication of the book may be significant, as the Islamic Republic authorities may have forced him into writing such statements under duress.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Ruhollah Khomeini said the government did not pay enough attention to religious figures which caused the coup d'état to take place and described the separation between religion and politics as a fault in contemporary history.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Ali Khamenei believed that Mosaddegh trusted the United States and asked them to help confront Britain.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Directed by Hasan Fathi and written jointly with playwright and university professor Naghmeh Samini, the TV series *Shahrzad* is the story of a love broken apart by events in the aftermath of the 1953 coup that overthrew the democratically elected prime minister, Mohammad Mosaddegh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1953-iranian-coup-d-état-p02] Cognito Comics/Verso Books has published a nonfiction graphic novel of the history, *Operation AJAX: The Story of the CIA Coup That Remade The Middle East*, that covers events leading to how the CIA hired rival mobs to create chaos and overthrow the country.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The **1979 Khuzestan uprising** was one of the nationwide uprisings in Iran which erupted in the aftermath of the Iranian revolution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The unrest was fed by Arab demands for autonomy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The uprising was effectively quelled by Iranian security forces, resulting in more than a hundred people on both sides killed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The Arabs of Iran are largely concentrated in the province of Khuzestan and number between half a million and 2 million.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] In Khuzestan, Arabs have historically formed the dominant ethnic group in Shadegan, Hoveyzeh and Susangerd, and a majority in Mahshahr, Khorramshahr, Abadan and Ahvaz.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The relationship between Iran's majority Persians and ethnic minorities changed when the Islamic Republic was formed in 1979.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] In part, this was a result of the Persian community's identification with the Islamic Republic, although some Arabs do identify with the Islamic republic as well.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] In 1978, Khuzestani Arab oil workers went on strike, cutting the supply of oil to Tehran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] This led to a reduction in income which contributed to the Shah's downfall and the Iranian Revolution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] Iranian clerics then encouraged hostility between Persians and Arabs.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] Following the aftermath of the Iranian revolution, Marxist guerrillas and federalist parties revolted in the regions of Khuzestan, Kurdistan and Gonbad-e Qabus, which resulted in fighting between various rebel groups and the forces loyal to the nascent revolutionary government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The largest rebellion by the Kurds unfolded in the West (Iranian Kurdistan), though the Revolutionary Guard (IRGC) was also confronted by Arabs, Turkomans and Baluchs.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] These revolts began in April 1979 and lasted between several months and over a year, depending on the region.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] In the early days of the communal conflict, the regime relied on volunteers from the Persian and Azeri communities to confront Kurdish, Baluchi and Turkoman rebellions.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] Khuzestani Arabs suffered economic and political marginalization by the Persian-dominated government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The uprising began when armed Sunni Arabs rebelled in late April and into May 1979.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] Other Arabs in Khuzestan began protests against discrimination, which prompted the regime to send IRGC units to assist the already deployed navy and air force personnel (in Khorramshahr) in quelling the violence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] Since rebellion broke out in Abadan, the Sepah was active in the arrests of Arabs and the confiscation of weapons.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] On May 29, an Arab protest in Khorramshahr was violently suppressed by the Revolutionary Guards.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] After 100 died in street fighting, Iran declared a state of emergency in Khuzestan on May 31.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] According to an EIR News Service issue from December 1979, while "half of Iran" was in rebellion, the situation in Khuzestan province had already calmed down, even though Arab and Bakhtiari tribes were reportedly at odds with Khomeini's regime.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] Although some Khuzestani Arabs initially aligned with the new revolutionary government in Tehran, they soon realized that the Islamic Republic under Ruhollah Khomenei intended to enforce the same policies of economic, political, and social marginalization as the previous regime of the Shah.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] More than a dozen Revolutionary Guardsmen and 100 Arabs died in the uprising.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] One of the consequences of the Arab uprising in Khuzestan was the Iranian Embassy siege, which took place from 30 April to 5 May 1980, after a group of six armed men stormed the Iranian embassy in South Kensington, London.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The gunmen took 26 people hostage—mostly embassy staff, but several visitors and a police officer, who had been guarding the embassy, were also held.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The hostage-takers were members of the DRFLA, an Iranian Arab militant group campaigning for the autonomy of Iran's Khuzestan province and they demanded the release of Arab prisoners from jails in Khūzestān and their own safe passage out of the United Kingdom.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The British government quickly resolved that safe passage would not be granted, and a siege ensued.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] During the 17-minute raid, the SAS rescued all but one of the remaining hostages and killed five of the six terrorists.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The soldiers subsequently faced accusations that they unnecessarily killed two of the terrorists, but an inquest into the deaths eventually cleared the SAS of any wrongdoing.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The remaining terrorist was prosecuted and served 27 years in British prisons.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] Later in 1980, The Khuzestan province has become a central scene of the Iran–Iraq War, which prompted the dimming of internal conflict, despite the Iraqi hopes of inciting a wide-scale rebellion by Arabs of Khuzestan, which eventually turned vague.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The tensions between the Iranian government and the Arab population of Khuzestan has sporadically exploded into violence over the next decades.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] In 2005, violent riots broke out in Khuzestan province, concentrating in the Ahvaz area.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] As a result, several people died and wide-scale arrests were performed by Iranian authorities.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] Following the events, a series of bombings were carried out in Khuzestan and in cities across Iran, claiming 28 casualties.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1979-khuzestan-insurgency] The responsibility for the bombings was claimed by Ahvaz Arab separatists.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The **1981–1982 Iran massacres** were a state-sponsored campaign of violence aimed at exterminating political and religious adversaries of the Islamic Republic of Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] It followed a period of unrest and protests that culminated in the June 28, 1981 bombing at the Islamic Republican Party headquarters, in which 74 leading officials of the Islamic Republic of Iran were killed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The subsequent period of retaliations became known as the "**reign of terror**".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The victims included intellectuals, scientists, artists, socialists, social democrats, members and sympathizers of Mujahedin-e-Khalq, nationalists, liberals, monarchists, ethnic minorities, and followers of minority religions such as the Bahá'í Faith.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] It was largely fueled by the Iranian Cultural Revolution decreed by Ruhollah Khomeini on 14 June 1980, with the intent of "purifying" Iranian society of non-Islamic elements.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] In July 2024, the UN Special Rapporteur on Human Rights in Iran published a landmark report on the 1981 massacre and categorised the atrocity crimes committed in 1981 and 1982 as genocide and crimes against humanity.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] In this report, the Rapporteur called for the establishment of an independent and international accountability mechanism.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The 1981 massacre in Iran occurred two years after the 1979 revolution, under the pretext of Islamizing the political and legal systems in the newly established Islamic Republic.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The government, led by Ayatollah Khomeini, sought to implement a theocratic framework based on his interpretations of Shia Islam and the doctrine of *velayat-e faqih*.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Aiming to transform Iranian society into a Shi'ite theocracy, Khomeini issued several fatwas and executive orders to "purify" public institutions and higher education from Marxist, non-Islamic, Western, and liberal influences.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The massacre was carried out under the cover of the Iranian Cultural Revolution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Initiated by an order from Ayatollah Khomeini on June 14, 1980, the revolution sought to remove Western, liberal, and leftist elements from the education system, leading to the closure of universities, the banning of student unions, and violent occupations of campuses.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] During this period, Shia clerics imposed policies to Islamize Iranian society, mandating hijabs for women, expelling critical academics, suppressing secular political groups, and persecuting intellectuals and artists.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] These measures sparked large-scale protests across the country.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] On June 15, 1981, the National Front and other secular opposition groups publicly criticized a proposal to Islamify the criminal justice system, prompting Ayatollah Khomeini to issue a fatwā, which led to the mass arrest of hundreds of protesters and critics.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] On June 20th, a large anti-government protest organized by the People's Mojahedin Organization of Iran responded to the controversial impeachment of President Abolhassan Banisadr.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Authorities announced that demonstrators, of any age, would be labeled 'enemies of God'.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps shot into crowds of protestors, resulting in around fifty deaths and over 200 injuries.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] In response to the growing waves of protests, clerics reacted ferociously.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Ayatollah Khomeini made several religious statements against critics, characterizing them as apostates (*murtad*), "anti-Islam" communists (*zed-e Islam*), atheists (*kafir*), and religious hypocrites (*munafiqs*).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Following Khomeini's order, hundreds of young protestors (including teenage girls) and critics were arrested, many sentenced to death by the Islamic Revolutionary Courts.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] On 21 June 1981, Saeed Soltanpour, a prominent poet and playwright, along with 14 other leftist dissidents, were summarily executed on charges of 'enmity against Islam, Allah, and his prophet' and 'spreading corruption on earth'.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Their executions marked the beginning of the largest wave of mass executions that the country would witness in its recent history.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Between June 1981 to March 1982, thousands of dissidents were subjected to systematic torture, summary, and arbitrary executions on religiously motivated charges of *moharebeh* ('enmity against Allah'), *ifsad-fil-arz* ('spreading corruption on Earth'), and *irtidad* (apostasy).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] On June 28, the Islamic Republic's opponents, allegedly, retaliated with a bombing at the IRP headquarters.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] This period in Iran became known as the "reign of terror".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] While the actual extent of 1981 massacre is still unknown, Rastyad Collective has verified and documented the identities of more than 3,500 victims who were executed between 21 June 1981 and 21 March 1982 in 85 cities.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] This data is based on more than 250 official documents from judiciary and political authorities, including statements and press releases issued by the Islamic Revolutionary Courts and the Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps (IRGC) in these cities.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Many victims of state violence during the 1981 massacre were below the age of eighteen.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] At least 103 individuals, accounting for 10% of identified victims, killed or executed in Tehran were minors.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Many of these underage victims were subjected to arbitrary detention, brutal torture, and summary executions on charges of *moharebeh* (enmity against Allah) and *ifsad-fil-arz* (spreading corruption on Earth).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] These figures and findings were highlighted by a landmark UN report by the UN Special Rapporteur on the Human Rights Situation in Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Other academic sources have offered similar estimates concerning the scope of the massacre.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] During this period the government carried out coordinated attacks against the civilian population through a state policy aimed at eliminating groups that were viewed as a threat.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] This included a wide range of Iranian citizens targeted due to their actual or suspected opposition to the Islamic Republic.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] According to official records the Iranian government labeled all its political opponents as "*moharebs*," "*mufsids*," counterrevolutionaries, "hypocrites," terrorists, "apostates," or pro-Western mercenaries.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] State-sponsored violence was not directed at a single group but aimed to eliminate a wide range of political ideologies that could challenge the state.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] These included liberals, nationalists, ethnic minorities, communists, Mujahedin-e Khalq (the largest opposition group), socialists, social democrats, monarchists, or followers of the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] During the massacre, hundreds of minors were also subjected to arbitrary detention, torture, and summary executions on ideologically motivated charges of *ifsad-fi-alarz* and *moharebeh* by the revolutionary courts.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Between June 1981 and March 1982, the highest proportion of executions were of individuals aged 11 to 24.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Most of these young activists were high school students or recent graduates from universities in Iran and abroad.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Data also shows that over 10% of the victims were minors—under 18 years old.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The youngest among them were Amrollah Kordi-Loo (1970-1981) and Elaheh Mohabbat (1965-1981), who were executed at 11 and 15 years old.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] In the context of Iran's modern social and historical situation, the execution of minors was an unprecedented and contentious event.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The ruling clerics intended to dismantle any prospects of blending modernism with Islam, a vision once idealistically pursued by President Banisadr.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Even though Banisadr's father, Ayatollah Seyed Nasrollah Banisadr, had been "an Islamic leader revered by Khomeini", clerics saw him as a potentially dangerous Western, secular influence within the revolutionary government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] A three-man presidential council was formed in 1981.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The council was headed by Ayatollah Mohammad Beheshti, with Akbar Rafsanjani and Mohammad-Ali Rajai as the other members.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Mohammad Mohammadi Gilani was one of the judges that handed out death sentences to protestors.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] During a press conference, Gilani justified the trials and executions of the young girls, stating, "By the Islamic canon, a nine-year-old girl is mature.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] In a TV interview, Tehran Revolutionary Prosecutor Asadollah Lajevardi acknowledged that flogging and physical punishment were employed as effective strategies to promote "repentance" and to help integrate "political prisoners into the Islamic Republics order".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] This methodical use of torture aimed to alter prisoners' religious beliefs, political views, and worldviews, while also pressuring them to make false public confessions.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The 1981-1982 massacre marked a pivotal period when Sharia judges in Iran gained the power to define and enforce their interpretation of "Islamic justice".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Those arrested were not allowed legal assistance, and confessions could be obtained under torture.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The large-scale execution of children breached Article 6(5) of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights, which Iran had ratified in 1975.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Similarly, Nasiri observes that more than ninety percent of the victims came from the Mojahedin and various Marxist groups.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] After a series of decrees and statements from Khomeini and other high-ranking clerics, these dissidents were labeled religious outlaws.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Marxists, because of their atheistic or non-theistic beliefs, were broadly classified as “apostate” (*murtad*) or “atheist” (*mulhid*) communists.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Between 1980 and 1983, Khomeini issued multiple decrees and fatwās targeting communists, identifying them as infidels (*kafir*) and apostate “mini-groups” (*gorouhak-haye murtad*).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] The Mojahedin were categorized as Munafiqin, an anti-Islam faction threatening both Islam and clerical authority.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Based on these religious classifications, supporters of the Mojahedin and Marxist groups were subjected to systematic extermination.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] According to Nasiri and Rehman, the explicit theological rationale behind official decrees supporting these killings provide grounds for interpreting them as acts of religious genocide.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Rastyad Collective has documented over 3,500 executions in 85 different cities that were carried out between June 1981 to March 1982.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] Moreover, the Rastyad Collective has documented the grave locations and identities of over 1,000 executed victims in Tehran's largest cemetery, Behesht-e Zahra.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1981-1982-iran-massacres] These findings are based on archival research, fieldwork, legal analysis and geolocation techniques.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] On 31 July 1987, during the Hajj (Arabic for pilgrimage) in Mecca, a clash between Shia pilgrim demonstrators and the Saudi Arabian security forces resulted in the death of more than 400 people.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The event has been variously described as a "riot" or a "massacre".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] It developed from increasing tensions between Shia Iran and Sunni Saudi Arabia since the 1979 Iranian Revolution.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] This escalated into a violent clash, followed by a deadly stampede.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] How many pilgrims died and how they died are both disputed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Both Iran and Saudi Arabia blame each other for the loss of life.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Estimates of fatalities range from 400 with thousands more injured (Iranian government); 402, of which 275 were Iranian pilgrims, 85 Saudi police, and 42 pilgrims from other countries (Saudi government); and more than 400 dead (*The New York Times*).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Saudis claim the pilgrims were armed and died in a stampede.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Iranians claim many were killed by Saudi gunfire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] After the incident, Iranians attacked the Saudi, Kuwaiti and French embassies in Tehran, abducting four Saudi diplomats.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Iran and Saudi Arabia have been called "bitter regional rivals" on "opposing sides of bloody conflicts in Syria, Yemen, and Iraq".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] This is in part for theological reasons—namely the differences between the two Islamic schools of thought that their governments adhere to.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The Wahhabi sect of Sunni Islam has both long supported the ruling House of Saud of the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, and long opposed Shi'i Islam as a sect deviant from true Islam.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Iranian Shia majority and Shi'i government were well aware of Wahhabi antagonism towards them and the "history of mistrust" between Shi'i pilgrims and Sunni hosts "stretches back as far as the sixteenth century".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Adding to this was the revolutionary antagonism of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini and his anti-American, anti-monarchy Iranian Revolutionary followers against the pro-American royal rulers of Saudi Arabia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In a 1987 public address Khomeini declared that "these vile and ungodly Wahhabis are like daggers which have always pierced the heart of the Muslims from the back".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] He announced that Mecca was in the hands of "a band of heretics", (i.e. the House of Saud).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Additionally, the incident occurred during the last phase of the Iran–Iraq War (1980–1988).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Although, at least from the Iraqi side, the conflict was not primarily religious, Saddam Hussein's government did play into concerns by Sunni rulers in the region who relied on religious authority for their position in order to gain their support.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] This provided fertile ground for sectarian tensions between Saudi Arabia (who started supporting Iraq) and Iran leading up to the events in 1987.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In 2015, an estimated 2,400 pilgrims, including more than 400 Iranians, were killed in a stampede, that led to a "war of words" between Iran and Saudi Arabia that reached a "fever pitch".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] For years, Iranian pilgrims had tried to stage demonstrations which are known as "Distancing Ourselves from Mushrikīn" (برائت از مشرکين) in the Muslim holy city of Mecca during the *hajj*.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] "Anti shah, anti-Israel and anti-American propaganda during the Hajj" by devotees of Khomeini had been happening since about 1971.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] These demonstrations had their origins in 1971, when Ruhollah Khomeini instructed his Shiite followers to distribute political messages when performing their pilgrimage.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Even though a few Iranians were arrested for this act, the Saudi officials were generally apathetic, as they did not view these political messages to be a threat to the Saudi royalty.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] After the revolution, following the principles elaborated by Khomeini, they appealed directly to the Muslim pilgrims of other lands gradually heightening political activity in each pilgrimage.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Iran claimed that "the Hajj and the Holy places should be placed under international oversight as opposed to being managed by the Saudis alone".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The Saudi government reacted to these disturbances with increasing concern because "the Hajj is an important legitimizing factor for the Saudi ruling family".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The first major confrontation between Shia pilgrims and Saudi security forces occurred in 1981.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In 1981, this was escalated to chanting political slogans in the Masjid al-Haram and the Prophet's Mosque, two of the holiest sites in Islam, resulting in violent clashes with Saudi security and one death.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In the same year, King Khalid of Saudi Arabia wrote a letter to Saddam Hussein saying "crush these stupid Iranians" as Saddam continued with the invasion of Iranian territory.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In 1982, Khomeini appointed Hojatoleslam Mohammad Mousavi Khoeiniha as the supervisor and personal representative of Ayatollah Khomeini.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Khoeiniha was the "mentor" of the students who had seized the United States Embassy in the Iran hostage crisis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] During the hajj that year, Saudi police clashed with demonstrators who Khoiniha addressed in both Medina and Mecca.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In Mecca he was arrested, and after giving a speech in Medina following the pilgrimage he was declared an “instigator” and expelled from Saudi Arabia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] During the next few years, both sides tried to calm the situation: Khomeini urged his devotees to maintain peace and order, not to distribute printed political material, and not to criticize Muslim governments.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In return, Saudi officials changed their earlier policy and allowed two separate demonstrations to occur: One in Mecca, and the other in Medina.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] By 1986, the situation was calm enough for Saudi officials to re-open the al-Baqi' cemetery for Shiite pilgrims, and in response, Khomeini's representative formally thanked the Saudi King for the gesture.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] However, in the same year, Iranian radical Mehdi Hashemi was accused of smuggling explosives on an airplane headed for Saudi Arabia, renewing Saudi fears.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Internationally, U.S. naval forces were being introduced into the Persian Gulf during this time in response to the Iran–Iraq War and heightening political tensions.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] According to the speech early in July 1987, Mohammad Mousavi Khoeiniha said that "a mere march or demonstration by Iranians will not suffice".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] He demanded that the Saudi regime allow Iranian pilgrims to enter the Great Mosque in Mecca at the end of their demonstration, without the presence of security guards.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Then a representative of Khomeini would explain Iran’s case regarding the Iran–Iraq War and an Iranian pilgrimage representative would conduct a referendum among all the pilgrims over the decision of the emir of Kuwait to invite foreign escorts for Kuwaiti tankers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] "All we ask is that the Saudi government not oppose this, nor send its guards to the Great Mosque.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Even though Mehdi Karrubi, who was Khomeini's official pilgrimage representative that year, tried to assure Saudi officials that the demonstrations would occur in the usual manner and in the agreed routes, it did little to quell the Saudi fears.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Saudis and Iranians worked together to go over "the route of the planned demonstration".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] As a result of dialogue and strict regulations which were imposed after it, it was agreed that "the demonstration would end half a kilometer before the great Mosque", but the decision "put the Saudi security forces on a high state of alert", and Saudi authorities "remained deeply suspicious".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] On Friday 31 July 1987, the demonstration started amid heightened security after Friday's midday prayers, while Iranian pilgrims chanted "Death to America!
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The march was uneventful until the end of the planned route when the demonstrators found their way blocked by Saudi riot police and National Guardsmen.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] At this point, some of the Iranians began to call for the demonstrators to press ahead and continue to the Great Mosque, at the same time "unidentified persons in an adjacent parking garage" began to throw "bricks, pieces of concrete, and iron bars" at the Iranians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] These events angered the Iranians, escalating the situation into a violent clash between the Iranian pilgrims and the Saudi security forces.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The Saudis reportedly used truncheons and electric prods and the Iranians reportedly used knives and clubs.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Saudi security personnel deny firing at the demonstrators, Saudi officials insist that no shots were fired, and that all deaths were caused by the melee and stampede.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In a Washington news conference, the Saudi ambassador Prince Bandar bin Sultan claimed that "not one bullet was fired", blaming the violence on the Iranian pilgrims who he accused of "brandishing knives, clubs and broken glass drawn from beneath their cloaks".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Iranian officials maintain that the Saudis had fired on the protesters without provocation and that the demonstrations had been peaceful.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Martin Kramer also writes that "according to American intelligence sources, the tide was finally turned by reinforcements from the National Guard, who fired tear gas shells into the crowd and then opened fire with pistols and automatic weapons".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The rioting and the resulting stampede reportedly caused the death of 402 people (275 Iranians, 85 Saudis, including policemen, and 42 pilgrims from other countries) and 649 people were reportedly wounded (303 Iranians, 145 Saudis and 201 other nationals).
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The Iranian news agency announced that "200 Iranians had been killed and more than 2,000 wounded".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Martin Kramer states that the Iranian authorities claimed that 400 Iranian pilgrims died, and that several thousand were injured.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] After the incident, Ali Khamenei, then president of Iran, declared that "they are now propagandizing and claiming that this incident was a war between Shia and Sunni.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Another high level Iranian leader, Ayatollah Hussein Ali Montazeri, urged Muslim religious leaders to "wrest control of Islam's holy sites in Saudi Arabia from the royal family".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In Iraq, the Revolutionary Command Council, ostensibly an organ of the secular Baath Arab socialist party, demanded that visiting of Islam's holy sites by Iranians should be banned.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The Iranian-backed Hezbollah in Lebanon asked Saudi Arabia to "pay for the deaths of the Shiite pilgrims".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] On 3 August 1987, one million Iranians converged on the building of the Islamic Council in Tehran, screaming "Revenge!
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Revenge!" in a rally "marking what was officially described as 'a day of hate,' according to the official Islamic Republic News Agency".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] On the same day, the Iranian leader Khomeini called on Saudis to overthrow the House of Saud to avenge the pilgrims' deaths.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] For three years after the incident—from 1988 to 1990—the Iranian government banned Iranians from going on the Hajj but "diplomatic ties were restored in 1991".
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Following the incident, Saudi Arabia ended its diplomatic relations with Iran and it reduced the number of permitted Iranian pilgrims to 45,000, down from 150,000 in earlier years.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] In 1991, Iran and Saudi Arabia renewed diplomatic relations after agreeing to allow Iranian pilgrims to perform the Hajj once more.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] The total number of pilgrims was set at 115,000, and the demonstrations by Iranians were again allowed, but only in one specific location granted by the Saudis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] By this agreement, Iranian pilgrims continued their annual demonstration during the 1990s and 2000s with few or no incidents.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] They limited their rally to within the confines of their compound in Mecca.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Approximately 20,000 Pakistani troops who were stationed in Saudi Arabia were sent back to Pakistan, because Saudi Arabia was uncomfortable with the presence of Shi'ite soldiers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/1987-mecca-incident] Martin Kramer writes that "as no independent investigation will ever be conducted, important details will remain in doubt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The **Achaemenid Empire** (/ə.ˈkiː.mə.nɪd/, *ə-KEE-mə-nid*; Old Persian: 𐎧𐏁𐏂, *Xšāça*, lit.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] 'The Empire' or 'The Kingdom') was an ancient Iranian empire founded by Cyrus the Great of the Achaemenid dynasty in 550 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] At peak, its territorial extent was roughly 5.5 million square kilometres (2.1 million square miles), making it the largest empire of its time.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Based in the Iranian plateau, it stretched from the Balkans and Cyrenaica in the west to the Indus Valley in the east, including Anatolia, Cyprus, Mesopotamia, the Levant, the South Caucasus, parts of Eastern Arabia, and large parts of Central Asia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the 7th century BC, the region of Persis, located in the southwestern part of the Iranian plateau, had been settled by Persian people.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persis, Cyrus rose and defeated Media, Lydia, and the Neo-Babylonian Empire, thus marking the establishment of a new imperial polity in the ancient Near East.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] While its conquests were largely successful in most regions, the Achaemenid Empire's attempts to expand into Greece proved extremely difficult over the course of decades of wars and multiple kings, ultimately resulting in its defeat in the Greek mainland.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 330 BC, amidst a Greek military campaign that began in 336 BC, the Achaemenid Empire was conquered in its entirety by Alexander the Great, who annexed it to his Macedonian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death, which sparked the beginning of the Hellenistic period in 323 BC, the majority of the former Achaemenid Empire's territories came under the rule of the Seleucid Empire and the Ptolemaic Kingdom.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Almost a century later, Iranian elites in the central plateau successfully reclaimed power from the Seleucids and established the Parthian Empire, which existed for nearly half a millennium before being succeeded by the Iranian Sasanian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of these systems were adopted and expanded upon by later empires in the Greco-Roman world and beyond.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire is named after Achaemenes, who is credited as the progenitor of the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The term *Achaemenid* means "of the family of the Achaemenis/Achaemenes" (Old Persian: 𐏃𐎧𐎠𐎶𐎴𐎡𐏁, romanized: *Haxāmaniš*; a bahuvrihi compound translating to "having a friend's mind").
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Achaemenes was himself a minor seventh-century ruler of the Anshan in southwestern Iran, and a vassal of Assyria.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Around 850 BC the original nomadic people who began the empire called themselves the *Parsa* and their constantly shifting territory *Parsua*, for the most part localized around Persis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The name "Persia" is a Greek and Latin pronunciation of the native word referring to the country of the people originating from Persis (Old Persian: 𐎱𐎠𐎼𐎿, romanized: *Pārsa*).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian term 𐎧𐏁𐏂 *Xšāça*, literally meaning "The Kingdom", was used to refer to the Empire formed by their multinational state.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire was created by nomadic Persians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were Iranian people who arrived in what is today Iran c.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] 1000 BC and settled a region including north-western Iran, the Zagros Mountains and Persis alongside the native Elamites.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians were originally nomadic pastoralists in the western Iranian Plateau.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid Empire may not have been the first Iranian empire, as the Medes, another group of Iranian people, possibly established a short-lived empire when they played a major role in overthrowing the Assyrians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids were initially rulers of the Elamite city of Anshan near the modern city of Marvdasht; the title "King of Anshan" was an adaptation of the earlier Elamite title "King of Susa and Anshan".
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] There are conflicting accounts of the identities of the earliest Kings of Anshan.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Cyrus Cylinder (the oldest extant genealogy of the Achaemenids) the kings of Anshan were Teispes, Cyrus I, Cambyses I and Cyrus II, also known as Cyrus the Great, who founded the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The later Behistun Inscription, written by Darius the Great, claims that Teispes was the son of Achaemenes and that Darius is also descended from Teispes through a different line, but no earlier texts mention Achaemenes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In Herodotus' Histories, he writes that Cyrus the Great was the son of Cambyses I and Mandane of Media, the daughter of Astyages, the king of the Median Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus revolted against the Median Empire in 553 BC, and in 550 BC succeeded in defeating the Medes, capturing Astyages and taking the Median capital city of Ecbatana.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Once in control of Ecbatana, Cyrus styled himself as the successor to Astyages and assumed control of the entire empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] By inheriting Astyages' empire, he also inherited the territorial conflicts the Medes had with both Lydia and the Neo-Babylonian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] King Croesus of Lydia sought to take advantage of the new international situation by advancing into what had previously been Median territory in Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus led a counterattack which not only fought off Croesus' armies, but also led to the capture of Sardis and the fall of the Lydian Kingdom in 546 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus placed Pactyes in charge of collecting tribute in Lydia and left, but once Cyrus had left Pactyes instigated a rebellion against Cyrus.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus sent the Median general Mazares to deal with the rebellion, and Pactyes was captured.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mazares, and after his death Harpagus, set about reducing all the cities which had taken part in the rebellion.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Lydia took about four years in total.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the power in Ecbatana changed hands from the Medes to the Persians, many tributaries to the Median Empire believed their situation had changed and revolted against Cyrus.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This forced Cyrus to fight wars against Bactria and the nomadic Saka in Central Asia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] During these wars, Cyrus established several garrison towns in Central Asia, including the Cyropolis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nothing is known of Persia–Babylon relations between 547 and 539 BC, but it is likely that there were hostilities between the two empires for several years leading up to the war of 540–539 BC and the Fall of Babylon.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In October 539 BC, Cyrus won a battle against the Babylonians at Opis, then took Sippar without a fight before finally capturing the city of Babylon on 12 October, where the Babylonian king Nabonidus was taken prisoner.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus is credited with freeing the Jews from the Babylonian captivity, permitting their return to Judah, and authorizing the rebuilding of Jerusalem, including the Second Temple.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 530 BC, Cyrus died and was succeeded by his eldest son Cambyses II, while his younger son Bardiya received a large territory in Central Asia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] By 525 BC, Cambyses had successfully subjugated Phoenicia and Cyprus and was making preparations to invade Egypt with the newly created Persian navy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Pharaoh Amasis II had died in 526, and had been succeeded by Psamtik III, resulting in the defection of key Egyptian allies to the Persians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Psamtik positioned his army at Pelusium in the Nile Delta.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] He was soundly defeated by the Persians in the Battle of Pelusium before fleeing to Memphis, where the Persians defeated him and took him prisoner.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After attempting a failed revolt, Psamtik III promptly committed suicide.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus depicts Cambyses as openly antagonistic to the Egyptian people and their gods, cults, temples, and priests, in particular stressing the murder of the sacred bull Apis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] He says that these actions led to a madness that caused him to kill his brother Bardiya (who Herodotus says was killed in secret), his own sister-wife and Croesus of Lydia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then concludes that Cambyses completely lost his mind, and all later classical authors repeat the themes of Cambyses' impiety and madness.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, this is based on spurious information, as the epitaph of Apis from 524 BC shows that Cambyses participated in the funeral rites of Apis styling himself as pharaoh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following the conquest of Egypt, the Libyans and the Greeks of Cyrene and Barca in present-day eastern Libya (Cyrenaica) surrendered to Cambyses and sent tribute without a fight.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cambyses then planned invasions of Carthage, the oasis of Ammon and Ethiopia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus claims that the naval invasion of Carthage was canceled because the Phoenicians, who made up a large part of Cambyses' fleet, refused to take up arms against their own people, but modern historians doubt whether an invasion of Carthage was ever planned at all.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, Cambyses dedicated his efforts to the other two campaigns, aiming to improve the Empire's strategic position in Africa by conquering the Kingdom of Meroë and taking strategic positions in the western oases.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] To this end, he established a garrison at Elephantine consisting mainly of Jewish soldiers, who remained stationed at Elephantine throughout Cambyses' reign.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Furthermore, in two inscriptions of Darius, Nubia is listed as one of the lands in the empire, and a Nubian delegation is depicted in Persepolis on the Apadana reliefs which visually present the lands of Darius’ empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] These suggest that Cambyses saw success in subduing Nubia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The events surrounding Cambyses's death and Bardiya's succession are greatly debated as there are many conflicting accounts.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to Herodotus, as Bardiya's assassination had been committed in secret, the majority of Persians still believed him to be alive.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This allowed two Magi to rise up against Cambyses, with one of them sitting on the throne able to impersonate Bardiya because of their remarkable physical resemblance and shared name (Smerdis in Herodotus's accounts).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ctesias writes that when Cambyses had Bardiya killed he immediately put the magus Sphendadates in his place as satrap of Bactria due to a remarkable physical resemblance.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Two of Cambyses' confidants then conspired to usurp Cambyses and put Sphendadates on the throne under the guise of Bardiya.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun Inscription, written by the following king Darius the Great, a magus named Gaumata impersonated Bardiya and incited a revolution in Persia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Whatever the exact circumstances of the revolt, Cambyses heard news of it in the summer of 522 BC and began to return from Egypt, but he was wounded in the thigh in Syria and died of gangrene, so Bardiya's impersonator became king.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The account of Darius is the earliest, and although the later historians all agree on the key details of the story, that a magus impersonated Bardiya and took the throne, this may have been a story created by Darius to justify his own usurpation.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Iranologist Pierre Briant hypothesises that Bardiya was not killed by Cambyses, but waited until his death in the summer of 522 BC to claim his legitimate right to the throne as he was then the only male descendant of the royal family.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Briant says that although the hypothesis of a deception by Darius is generally accepted today, "nothing has been established with certainty at the present time, given the available evidence".
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] According to the Behistun inscription, Gaumata ruled for seven months before being overthrown in 522 BC by Darius the Great (Old Persian *Dāryavuš*, "who holds firm the good", also known as *Darayarahush*).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Magi, though persecuted, continued to exist, and a year following the death of the first pseudo-Smerdis (*Gaumata*), saw a second pseudo-Smerdis (*Vahyazdāta*) attempt a coup.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The coup, though initially successful, failed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus writes that the native leadership debated the best form of government for the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Macedonian king Amyntas I surrendered his country to the Persians in about 512–511.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The subjugation of Macedonia was part of Persian military operations initiated by Darius the Great (521–486) in 513—after immense preparations—a huge Achaemenid army invaded the Balkans and tried to defeat the European Scythians roaming to the north of the Danube river.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' army subjugated several Thracian people, and virtually all other regions that touch the European part of the Black Sea, such as parts of modern Bulgaria, Romania, Ukraine, and Russia, before it returned to Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius left in Europe one of his commanders named Megabazus whose task was to accomplish conquests in the Balkans.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian troops subjugated gold-rich Thrace, the coastal Greek cities, and defeated and conquered the powerful Paeonians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Finally, Megabazus sent envoys to Amyntas, demanding acceptance of Persian domination, which the Macedonians did.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Balkans provided many soldiers for the multi-ethnic Achaemenid army.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Many of the Macedonian and Persian elite intermarried, such as the Persian official Bubares who married Amyntas' daughter, Gygaea.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Family ties that the Macedonian rulers Amyntas and Alexander enjoyed with Bubares ensured them good relations with the Persian kings Darius and Xerxes I, who was also known as Xerxes the Great.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian invasion led indirectly to Macedonia's rise in power and Persia had some common interests in the Balkans; with Persian aid, the Macedonians stood to gain much at the expense of some Balkan tribes such as the Paeonians and Greeks.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] All in all, the Macedonians were "willing and useful Persian allies.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Macedonian soldiers fought against Athens and Sparta in Xerxes I's army.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians referred to both Greeks and Macedonians as *Yauna* ("Ionians", their term for "Greeks"), and to Macedonians specifically as *Yaunã Takabara* or "Greeks with hats that look like shields", possibly referring to the Macedonian kausia hat.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt in 499 BC, and associated revolts in Aeolis, Doris, Cyprus, and Caria, were military rebellions by several regions of Asia Minor against Persian rule, lasting from 499 to 493 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the heart of the rebellion was the dissatisfaction of the Greek cities of Asia Minor with the tyrants appointed by Persia to rule them, along with the individual actions of two Milesian tyrants, Histiaeus and Aristagoras.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 499 BC, the then-tyrant of Miletus, Aristagoras, launched a joint expedition with the Persian satrap Artaphernes to conquer Naxos, in an attempt to bolster his position in Miletus, both financially and in terms of prestige.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The mission was a debacle, and sensing his imminent removal as a tyrant, Aristagoras chose to incite the whole of Ionia into rebellion against the Persian king, Darius I, who was commonly known as Darius the Great.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persians continued to reduce the cities along the west coast that still held out against them, before finally imposing a peace settlement in 493 BC on Ionia that was generally considered to be both just and fair.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ionian Revolt constituted the first major conflict between Greece and the Achaemenid Empire, and as such represents the first phase of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Asia Minor had been brought back into the Persian fold, but Darius had vowed to punish Athens and Eretria for their support of the revolt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Moreover, seeing that the political situation in Greece posed a continued threat to the stability of his Empire, he decided to embark on the conquest of all of Greece.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The first campaign of the invasion was to bring the territories in the Balkan peninsula back within the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian grip over these territories had loosened following the Ionian Revolt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 492 BC, the Persian general Mardonius re-subjugated Thrace and made Macedonia a fully subordinate part of the empire; it had been a vassal as early as the late 6th century BC but retained a great deal of autonomy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 490 BC the Persian forces were defeated by the Athenians at the Battle of Marathon and Darius I would die before having the chance to launch an invasion of Greece.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes I (485–465 BC, Old Persian *Xšayārša* "Hero Among Kings"), son of Darius I, vowed to complete the job.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] He organized a massive invasion aiming to conquer Greece.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] His army entered Greece from the north in the spring of 480 BC, meeting little or no resistance through Macedonia and Thessaly, but was delayed by a small Greek force for three days at Thermopylae.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] A simultaneous naval battle of Artemisium was tactically indecisive as large storms destroyed ships from both sides.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was stopped prematurely when the Greeks received news of the defeat at Thermopylae and retreated.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The battle was a tactical victory for the Persians, giving them uncontested control of Artemisium and the Aegean Sea.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following his victory at the Battle of Thermopylae, Xerxes sacked the evacuated city of Athens and prepared to meet the Greeks at the strategic Isthmus of Corinth and the Saronic Gulf.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 480 BC the Greeks won a decisive victory over the Persian fleet at the Battle of Salamis and forced Xerxes to retire to Sardis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The land army which he left in Greece under Mardonius retook Athens but was eventually destroyed in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The final defeat of the Persians at Mycale encouraged the Greek cities of Asia to revolt, and the Persians lost all of their territories in Europe with Macedonia once again becoming independent.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Xerxes was assassinated in his bed, though ancient accounts conflict significantly.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The assassination is attributed by Greek and Roman sources to Artabanus, though a Babylonian tablet attributes it to Xerxes' son.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Xerxes I was assassinated, he was succeeded by his eldest surviving son Artaxerxes I.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was during his reign that Elamite ceased to be the language of government, and Aramaic gained in importance.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was probably during this reign that the solar calendar was introduced as the national calendar.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Artaxerxes I, Zoroastrianism became the *de facto* religion of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Persia had been defeated at the Battle of Eurymedon (469 or 466 BC), military action between Greece and Persia was halted.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes I took power, he introduced a new Persian strategy of weakening the Athenians by funding their enemies in Greece.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This indirectly caused the Athenians to move the treasury of the Delian League from the island of Delos to the Athenian acropolis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This funding practice inevitably prompted renewed fighting in 450 BC, where the Greeks attacked at the Battle of Cyprus.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After Cimon's failure to attain much in this expedition, the Peace of Callias was agreed between Athens, Argos and Persia in 449 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes offered asylum to Themistocles, who was the winner of the Battle of Salamis, after Themistocles was ostracized from Athens.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, Artaxerxes gave him Magnesia, Myus, and Lampsacus to maintain him in bread, meat, and wine.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In addition, Artaxerxes I gave him Palaescepsis to provide him with clothes, and he also gave him Percote with bedding for his house.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Artaxerxes died in 424 BC at Susa, his body was taken to the tomb already built for him in the Naqsh-e Rustam Necropolis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was Persian tradition that kings begin constructing their own tombs while they were still alive.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes I was immediately succeeded by his eldest and only legitimate son, Xerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, after a few days on the throne, he was assassinated while drunk by Pharnacyas and Menostanes on the orders of his illegitimate brother Sogdianus, who apparently had gained the support of his regions.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus reigned for six months and fifteen days before being captured by his half-brother, Ochus, who had rebelled against him.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sogdianus was executed by being suffocated in ash because Ochus had promised he would not die by the sword, by poison or by hunger.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Ochus then took the royal name Darius II.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius' ability to defend his position on the throne ended the short power vacuum.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] From 412 BC Darius II, at the insistence of Tissaphernes, gave support first to Athens, then to Sparta, but in 407 BC, Darius' son Cyrus the Younger was appointed to replace Tissaphernes and aid was given entirely to Sparta which finally defeated Athens in 404 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the same year, Darius fell ill and died in Babylon.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] His death gave an Egyptian rebel named Amyrtaeus the opportunity to throw off Persian control over Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] At his death bed, Darius' Babylonian wife Parysatis pleaded with him to have her second eldest son Cyrus (the Younger) crowned, but Darius refused.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Queen Parysatis favoured Cyrus more than her eldest son Artaxerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Plutarch relates (probably on the authority of Ctesias) that the displaced Tissaphernes came to the new king on his coronation day to warn him that his younger brother Cyrus (the Younger) was preparing to assassinate him during the ceremony.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had Cyrus arrested and would have had him executed if their mother Parysatis had not intervened.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus was then sent back as Satrap of Lydia, where he prepared an armed rebellion.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus assembled a large army, including a contingent of Ten Thousand Greek mercenaries, and made his way deeper into Persia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The army of Cyrus was stopped by the royal Persian army of Artaxerxes II at Cunaxa in 401 BC, where Cyrus was killed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Ten Thousand Greek Mercenaries including Xenophon were now deep in Persian territory and were at risk of attack.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] So they searched for others to offer their services to but eventually had to return to Greece.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II was the longest reigning of the Achaemenid kings and it was during this 45-year period of relative peace and stability that many of the monuments of the era were constructed.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes moved the capital back to Persepolis, which he greatly extended.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, the summer capital at Ecbatana was lavishly extended with gilded columns and roof tiles of silver and copper.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The extraordinary innovation of the Zoroastrian shrines can also be dated to his reign, and it was probably during this period that Zoroastrianism spread from Armenia throughout Asia Minor and the Levant.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The construction of temples, though serving a religious purpose, was not a purely selfless act, as they also served as an important source of income.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] From the Babylonian kings, the Achaemenids adopted the concept of a mandatory temple tax, a one-tenth tithe which all inhabitants paid to the temple nearest to their land or another source of income.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II became involved in a war with Persia's erstwhile allies, the Spartans, who, under Agesilaus II, invaded Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] To redirect the Spartans' attention to Greek affairs, Artaxerxes II subsidized their enemies: in particular the Athenians, Thebans and Corinthians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] These subsidies helped to engage the Spartans in what would become known as the Corinthian War.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 387 BC, Artaxerxes II betrayed his allies and came to an arrangement with Sparta, and in the Treaty of Antalcidas he forced his erstwhile allies to come to terms.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This treaty restored control of the Greek cities of Ionia and Aeolis on the Anatolian coast to the Persians while giving Sparta dominance on the Greek mainland.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 385 BC he campaigned against the Cadusians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although successful against the Greeks, Artaxerxes II had more trouble with the Egyptians, who had successfully revolted against him at the beginning of his reign.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] An attempt to reconquer Egypt in 373 BC was completely unsuccessful, but in his waning years the Persians did manage to defeat a joint Egyptian–Spartan effort to conquer Phoenicia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] He quashed the Revolt of the Satraps in 372–362 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] He is reported to have had a number of wives.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] His main wife was Stateira, until she was poisoned by Artaxerxes II's mother Parysatis in about 400 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Another chief wife was a Greek woman of Phocaea named Aspasia (not the same as the concubine of Pericles).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes II is said to have had more than 115 sons from 350 wives.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 358 BC Artaxerxes II died and was succeeded by his son Artaxerxes III.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 355 BC, Artaxerxes III forced Athens to conclude a peace which required the city's forces to leave Asia Minor and to acknowledge the independence of its rebellious allies.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes started a campaign against the rebellious Cadusians, but he managed to appease both of the Cadusian kings.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] One individual who successfully emerged from this campaign was Darius Codomannus, who later occupied the Persian throne as Darius III.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III then ordered the disbanding of all the satrapal armies of Asia Minor, as he felt that they could no longer guarantee peace in the west and was concerned that these armies equipped the western satraps with the means to revolt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The order was however ignored by Artabazos II of Phrygia, who asked for the help of Athens in a rebellion against the king.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes of Mysia also supported Artabazos and the combined forces managed to defeat the forces sent by Artaxerxes III in 354 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, in 353 BC, they were defeated by Artaxerxes III's army and were disbanded.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Orontes was pardoned by the king, while Artabazos fled to the safety of the court of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] 351 BC, Artaxerxes embarked on a campaign to recover Egypt, which had revolted under his father, Artaxerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] At the same time, a rebellion had broken out in Asia Minor, which, being supported by Thebes, threatened to become serious.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Levying a vast army, Artaxerxes invaded Egypt and engaged in fighting with Nectanebo II.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After a year of fighting the Egyptian Pharaoh, Nectanebo inflicted a crushing defeat on the Persians with the support of mercenaries led by the Greek generals Diophantus and Lamius.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes was compelled to retreat and postpone his plans to reconquer Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Soon after this defeat, there were rebellions in Phoenicia, Asia Minor and Cyprus.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] , with a label in Greek (ΔΑΡΕΙΟΣ, top right) giving his name.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes committed responsibility for the suppression of the Cyprian rebels to Idrieus, prince of Caria, who employed 8,000 Greek mercenaries and forty triremes, commanded by Phocion the Athenian, and Evagoras, son of the elder Evagoras, the Cypriot monarch.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes initiated a counter-offensive against Sidon by commanding Belesys, satrap of Syria, and Mazaeus, satrap of Cilicia, to invade the city and to keep the Phoenicians in check.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both satraps suffered crushing defeats at the hands of Tennes, the Sidonese king, who was aided by 40,000 Greek mercenaries sent to him by Nectanebo II and commanded by Mentor of Rhodes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persian forces were driven out of Phoenicia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this, Artaxerxes personally led an army of 330,000 men against Sidon.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes' army comprised 300,000-foot soldiers, 30,000 cavalry, 300 triremes, and 500 transports or provision ships.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After gathering this army, he sought assistance from the Greeks.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Though refused aid by Athens and Sparta, he succeeded in obtaining a thousand Theban heavy-armed hoplites under Lacrates, three thousand Argives under Nicostratus, and six thousand Æolians, Ionians, and Dorians from the Greek cities of Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Greek support was numerically small, amounting to no more than 10,000 men, but it formed, together with the Greek mercenaries from Egypt who went over to him afterward, the force on which he placed his chief reliance, and to which the ultimate success of his expedition was mainly due.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The approach of Artaxerxes sufficiently weakened the resolution of Tennes that he endeavoured to purchase his own pardon by delivering up 100 principal citizens of Sidon into the hands of the Persian king and then admitting Artaxerxes within the defences of the town.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes had the 100 citizens transfixed with javelins, and when 500 more came out as supplicants to seek his mercy, Artaxerxes consigned them to the same fate.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sidon was then burnt to the ground, either by Artaxerxes or by the Sidonian citizens.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Forty thousand people died in the conflagration.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes sold the ruins at a high price to speculators, who calculated on reimbursing themselves by the treasures which they hoped to dig out from among the ashes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tennes was later put to death by Artaxerxes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes later sent Jews who supported the revolt to Hyrcania on the south coast of the Caspian Sea.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The reduction of Sidon was followed closely by the invasion of Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 343 BC, Artaxerxes III, in addition to his 330,000 Persians, had now a force of 14,000 Greeks furnished by the Greek cities of Asia Minor: 4,000 under Mentor, consisting of the troops that he had brought to the aid of Tennes from Egypt; 3,000 sent by Argos; and 1,000 from Thebes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] He divided these troops into three bodies, and placed at the head of each a Persian and a Greek.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Greek commanders were Lacrates of Thebes, Mentor of Rhodes and Nicostratus of Argos while the Persians were led by Rhossaces, Aristazanes, and Bagoas, the chief of the eunuchs.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II resisted with an army of 100,000 of whom 20,000 were Greek mercenaries.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Nectanebo II occupied the Nile and its various branches with his large navy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The character of the country, intersected by numerous canals and full of strongly fortified towns, was in his favour and Nectanebo II might have been expected to offer a prolonged, if not even a successful resistance.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] However, he lacked good generals, and, over-confident in his own powers of command, he was out-maneuvered by the Greek mercenary generals, and his forces were eventually defeated by the combined Persian armies.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his defeat, Nectanebo hastily fled to Memphis, leaving the fortified towns to be defended by their garrisons.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] These garrisons consisted of partly Greek and partly Egyptian troops; between whom jealousies and suspicions were easily sown by the Persian leaders.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] As a result, the Persians were able to rapidly reduce numerous towns across Lower Egypt and were advancing upon Memphis when Nectanebo decided to quit the country and flee southwards to Ethiopia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian army completely routed the Egyptians and occupied the Lower Delta of the Nile.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Nectanebo fleeing to Ethiopia, all of Egypt submitted to Artaxerxes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Jews in Egypt were sent either to Babylon or to the south coast of the Caspian Sea, the same location that the Jews of Phoenicia had earlier been sent.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After this victory over the Egyptians, Artaxerxes had the city walls destroyed, started a reign of terror, and set about looting all the temples.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persia gained a significant amount of wealth from this looting.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes also raised high taxes and attempted to weaken Egypt enough that it could never revolt against Persia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] For the 10 years that Persia controlled Egypt, believers in the native religion were persecuted and sacred books were stolen.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Before Artaxerxes returned to Persia, he appointed Pherendares as satrap of Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] With the wealth gained from his reconquering Egypt, Artaxerxes was able to amply reward his mercenaries.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] He then returned to his capital having successfully completed his invasion of Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After his success in Egypt, Artaxerxes returned to Persia and spent the next few years effectively quelling insurrections in various parts of the Empire so that a few years after his conquest of Egypt, the Persian Empire was firmly under his control.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Egypt remained a part of the Persian Empire from then until Alexander the Great's conquest of Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] After the conquest of Egypt, there were no more revolts or rebellions against Artaxerxes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor and Bagoas, the two generals who had most distinguished themselves in the Egyptian campaign, were advanced to posts of the highest importance.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Mentor, who was governor of the entire Asiatic seaboard, was successful in reducing to subjection many of the chiefs who during the recent troubles had rebelled against Persian rule.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the course of a few years, Mentor and his forces were able to bring the whole Asian Mediterranean coast into complete submission and dependence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas went back to the Persian capital with Artaxerxes, where he took a leading role in the internal administration of the Empire and maintained tranquillity throughout the rest of the Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] During the last six years of the reign of Artaxerxes III, the Persian Empire was governed by a vigorous and successful government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian forces in Ionia and Lycia regained control of the Aegean and the Mediterranean Sea and took over much of Athens' former island empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, Isocrates of Athens started giving speeches calling for a 'crusade against the barbarians' but there was not enough strength left in any of the Greek city-states to answer his call.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Although there were no rebellions in the Persian Empire itself, the growing power and territory of Philip II of Macedon in Macedon (against which Demosthenes was in vain warning the Athenians) attracted the attention of Artaxerxes.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In response, he ordered that Persian influence was to be used to check and constrain the rising power and influence of the Macedonian kingdom.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 340 BC, a Persian force was dispatched to assist the Thracian prince, Cersobleptes, to maintain his independence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Sufficient effective aid was given to the city of Perinthus that the numerous and well-appointed army with which Philip had commenced his siege of the city was compelled to give up the attempt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] By the last year of Artaxerxes' rule, Philip II already had plans in place for an invasion of the Persian Empire, which would crown his career, but the Greeks would not unite with him.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 338 BC Artaxerxes was poisoned by Bagoas with the assistance of a physician.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Artaxerxes III was succeeded by Artaxerxes IV Arses, who before he could act was also poisoned by Bagoas.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas is further said to have killed not only all Arses' children, but many of the other princes of the land.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bagoas then placed Darius III, a nephew of Artaxerxes IV, on the throne.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III, previously the Satrap of Armenia, personally forced Bagoas to swallow poison.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In 334 BC, when Darius was just succeeding in subduing Egypt again, Alexander and his battle-hardened troops invaded Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander the Great (Alexander III of Macedon) defeated the Persian armies at Granicus (334 BC), followed by Issus (333 BC), and lastly at Gaugamela (331 BC).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Afterwards, he marched on Susa and Persepolis which surrendered and was destroyed by fire in early 330 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] From Persepolis, Alexander headed north to Pasargadae, where he visited the tomb of Cyrus, the man whom he had heard of from the *Cyropaedia*.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] In the ensuing chaos created by Alexander's invasion of Persia, Cyrus's tomb was broken into and most of its luxuries were looted.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] When Alexander reached the tomb, he was horrified by the manner in which it had been treated, and questioned the Magi, putting them on trial.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] By some accounts, Alexander's decision to put the Magi on trial was more an attempt to undermine their influence and display his own power than a show of concern for Cyrus's tomb.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Regardless, Alexander the Great ordered Aristobulus to improve the tomb's condition and restore its interior, showing respect for Cyrus.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] From there he headed to Ecbatana, where Darius III had sought refuge.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius III was taken prisoner by Bessus, his Bactrian satrap and kinsman.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] As Alexander approached, Bessus had his men murder Darius III and then declared himself Darius' successor, as Artaxerxes V, before retreating into Central Asia leaving Darius' body in the road to delay Alexander, who brought it to Persepolis for an honourable funeral.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Bessus would then create a coalition of his forces, to create an army to defend against Alexander.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alexander generally kept the original Achaemenid administrative structure, leading some scholars to dub him as "the last of the Achaemenids".
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Upon Alexander's death in 323 BC, his empire was divided among his generals, the Diadochi, resulting in a number of smaller states.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The largest of these, which held sway over the Iranian plateau, was the Seleucid Empire, ruled by Alexander's general Seleucus I Nicator.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Native Iranian rule would be restored by the Parthians of northeastern Iran over the course of the 2nd century BC through the Parthian Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Several later Persian rulers, forming the *Frataraka* dynasty, are known to have acted as representatives of the Seleucids in the region of Fārs.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] They ruled from the end of the 3rd century BC to the beginning of the 2nd century BC, and Vahbarz or Vādfradād I obtained independence c.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] 150 BC, when Seleucid power waned in the areas of southwestern Persia and the Persian Gulf region.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] During an apparent transitional period, corresponding to the reigns of Vādfradād II and another uncertain king, no titles of authority appeared on the reverse of their coins.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The earlier title *prtrk' zy alhaya* (Frataraka) had disappeared.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under Dārēv I (Darios I) however, the new title of *mlk*, or king, appeared, sometimes with the mention of *prs* (Persis), suggesting that the kings of Persis had become independent rulers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] When the Parthian Arsacid king Mithridates I (c.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] 171–138 BC) took control of Persis, he left the Persian dynasts in office, known as the Kings of Persis, and they were allowed to continue minting coins with the title of *mlk* ("King").
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenid line would also be carried on through the Kingdom of Pontus, based in the Pontus region of northern Asia Minor.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This Pontic Kingdom, a state of Persian origin, may even have been directly related to Darius I and the Achaemenid dynasty.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] It was founded by Mithridates I in 281 BC and lasted until its conquest by the Roman Republic in 63 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The kingdom grew to its largest extent under Mithridates VI the Great, who conquered Colchis, Cappadocia, Bithynia, the Greek colonies of the Tauric Chersonesos and for a brief time the Roman province of Asia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Thus, this Persian dynasty managed to survive and prosper in the Hellenistic world while the main Persian Empire had fallen.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Despite Greek influence on the Kingdom of Pontus, Pontics continued to maintain their Achaemenid lineage.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Both the later dynasties of the Parthians and Sasanians would on occasion claim Achaemenid descent.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Recently there has been some corroboration for the Parthian claim to Achaemenid ancestry via the possibility of an inherited disease (neurofibromatosis) demonstrated by the physical descriptions of rulers and from the evidence of familial disease on ancient coinage.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great founded the empire as a multi-state empire, governed from four capital cities: Pasargadae, Babylon, Susa and Ecbatana.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Achaemenids allowed a certain amount of regional autonomy in the form of the satrapy system.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] A satrapy was an administrative unit, usually organized on a geographical basis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] A 'satrap' (governor) was the governor who administered the region, a 'general' supervised military recruitment and ensured order, and a 'state secretary' kept the official records.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The general and the state secretary reported directly to the satrap as well as the central government.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] At differing times, there were between 20 and 30 satrapies.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Cyrus the Great created an organized army including the Immortals unit, consisting of 10,000 highly trained soldiers Cyrus also formed an innovative postal system throughout the empire, based on several relay stations called Chapar Khaneh.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Persepolis Administrative Archives provide many insights into the Achaemenid government system.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Found at Persepolis in the 1930s, they are mostly in Elamite; the remains of more than 10,000 of these cuneiform documents have been uncovered.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Aramaic is represented by about 1,000 or more original records.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Only one tablet in Old Persian has been identified so far.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Also, many seals and seal impressions are found in these Persepolis archives.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] These documents represent administrative activity and flow of data in Persepolis over more than fifty consecutive years (509–457 BC).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The Persian daric was the first gold coin which, along with a similar silver coin, the siglos, introduced the bimetallic monetary standard of the Achaemenids, which has continued until today.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was accomplished by Darius I, who reinforced the empire and expanded Persepolis as a ceremonial capital; he revolutionized the economy by placing it on the silver and gold coinage.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Darius also introduced a regulated and sustainable tax system that was precisely tailored to each satrapy, based on their supposed productivity and their economic potential.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] For instance, Babylon was assessed for the highest amount and for a startling mixture of commodities – 1,000 silver talents, four months' supply of food for the army.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] India was clearly already fabled for its gold; Egypt was known for the wealth of its crops; it was to be the granary of the Persian Empire (as later of Rome's) and was required to provide 120,000 measures of grain in addition to 700 talents of silver.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This was exclusively a tax levied on subject peoples.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] There is evidence that conquered and rebellious enemies could be sold into slavery.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Alongside its other innovations in administration and taxation, the Achaemenids may have been the first government in the ancient Near East to register private slave sales and tax them using an early form of sales tax.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Other accomplishments of Darius' reign included the codification of the *dāta* (a universal legal system which would become the basis of later Iranian law), and the construction of a new capital at Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Under the Achaemenids, trade was extensive and there was an efficient infrastructure that facilitated the exchange of commodities in the far reaches of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Tariffs on trade, along with agriculture and tribute, were major sources of revenue for the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The satrapies were linked by a 2,500-kilometer highway, the most impressive stretch being the Royal Road from Susa to Sardis, built under the command of Darius I.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] It connected the Iranian Plateau to Central Asia and the Mediterranean.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] It featured stations and caravanserais at specific intervals.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] The relays of mounted couriers (the angarium) could reach the remotest of areas in fifteen days.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Herodotus observes that "there is nothing in the world that travels faster than these Persian couriers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] Following Alexander's conquests, this highway allowed for the spread of cultural syncretic fusions like Greco-Buddhism into Central Asia and China, as well as empires like the Kushan, Indo-Greek and Parthian to profit from trade between East and West.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p01] This route was greatly rehabilitated and formalized during the Abbasid Caliphate, during which it developed into a major component of the famed Silk Road.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite its humble origins in Persis, the empire reached an enormous size under the leadership of Cyrus the Great.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus created a multi-state empire where he allowed regional rulers, satraps, to rule as his proxy over a certain designated area of his empire called a satrapy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The basic rule of governance was based upon loyalty and obedience of each satrapy to the central power, or the king, and compliance with tax laws.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus managed to create a strong land army, using it to advance in his campaigns in Babylonia, Lydia, and Asia Minor, which after his death was used by his son Cambyses II, in Egypt against Psamtik III.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus would die battling a local Iranian insurgency in the empire, before he could have a chance to develop a naval force.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] That task would fall to Darius I, who would officially give Persians their own royal navy to allow them to engage their enemies on multiple seas of this vast empire, from the Black Sea and the Aegean Sea, to the Persian Gulf, Ionian Sea and the Mediterranean Sea.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid infantry consisted of three groups: the Immortals, the Sparabara, and the Takabara, though in the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, a fourth group, the Cardaces, were introduced.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Immortals were described by Herodotus as being heavy infantry, led by Hydarnes II, that were kept constantly at a strength of exactly 10,000 men.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] He claimed that the unit's name stemmed from the custom that every killed, seriously wounded, or sick member was immediately replaced with a new one, maintaining the numbers and cohesion of the unit.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] They had wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, and bow and arrows.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Underneath their robes they wore scale armour coats.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The spear counterbalances of the common soldiery were of silver; to differentiate commanding ranks, the officers' spear butt-spikes were golden.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Surviving Achaemenid colored glazed bricks and carved reliefs represent the Immortals as wearing elaborate robes, hoop earrings and gold jewellery, though these garments and accessories were most likely worn only for ceremonial occasions.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were usually the first to engage in hand-to-hand combat with the enemy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although not much is known about them today, it is believed that they were the backbone of the Persian army who formed a shield wall and used their two-metre-long spears to protect more vulnerable troops such as archers from the enemy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Sparabara were taken from the full members of Persian society, were trained from childhood to be soldiers and when not called out to fight on campaigns in distant lands they practised hunting on the vast plains of Persia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, when all was quiet and the *Pax Persica* held true, the Sparabara returned to normal life farming the land and grazing their herds.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Because of this, they lacked true professional quality on the battlefield, yet they were well trained and courageous to the point of holding the line in most situations long enough for a counter-attack.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] They were armoured with quilted linen and carried large rectangular wicker shields as a form of light maneuverable defence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] This, however, left them at a severe disadvantage against heavily armoured opponents such as the hoplite, and their two-metre-long spear was not able to give the Sparabara ample range to plausibly engage a trained phalanx.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The wicker shields were able to effectively stop arrows but not strong enough to protect the soldier from spears.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, the Sparabara could deal with most other infantry, including trained units from the East.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenids relied heavily on archery.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Major contributing nations were the Scythians, Medes, Persians, and the Elamites.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The composite bow was used by the Persians and Medes, who adopted it from the Scythians and transmitted it to other nations, including the Greeks.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid armies typically used socketed, three-bladed (also known as trilobate or Scythian) arrowheads.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] These arrowheads were cast from leaded tin-bronze, which made them amenable to mass-production unlike the wrought iron arrowheads of the period that had to be individually forged.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were a rare unit who were a tough type of peltasts.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] They tended to fight with their own native weapons which would have included a crescent-shaped light wickerwork shield and axes as well as light linen cloth and leather.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Takabara were recruited from territories that incorporated modern Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian cavalry was crucial for conquering nations and maintained its importance in the Achaemenid army to the last days of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The cavalry was separated into four groups.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers, horse cavalry, the camel cavalry, and the war elephants.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the later years of the Achaemenid Empire, the chariot archer had become merely a ceremonial part of the Persian army, yet in the early years of the Empire, their use was widespread.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariot archers were armed with lances, bows, arrows, swords, and scale armour.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses were also suited with scale armour similar to scale armour of the Sassanian cataphracts.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chariots would contain imperial symbols and decorations.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The horses used by the Achaemenids for cavalry were often suited with scale armour, like most cavalry units.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The riders often had the same armour as Infantry units, wicker shields, short spears, swords or large daggers, bow and arrow, and scale armour coats.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was different, because the camels and sometimes the riders, were provided little protection against enemies, yet when they were offered protection, they would have lances, swords, bow, arrow, and scale armour.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The camel cavalry was first introduced into the Persian army by Cyrus the Great, at the Battle of Thymbra.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The elephant was most likely introduced into the Persian army by Darius I after his conquest of the Indus Valley.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Elephants may have been used in Greek campaigns by Darius and Xerxes I, but Greek accounts only mention 15 of them being used at the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Since its foundation by Cyrus, the Persian empire had been primarily a land empire with a strong army but void of any actual naval forces.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] By the 5th century BC, this was to change, as the empire came across Greek and Egyptian forces, each with their own maritime traditions and capabilities.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I was the first Achaemenid king to invest in a Persian fleet.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even by then no true "imperial navy" had existed either in Greece or Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persia would become the first empire, under Darius, to inaugurate and deploy the first regular imperial navy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Despite this achievement, the personnel for the imperial navy would not come from Iran, but were often Phoenicians (mostly from Sidon), Egyptians and Greeks chosen by Darius the Great to operate the empire's combat vessels.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] At first the ships were built in Sidon by the Phoenicians; the first Achaemenid ships measured about 40 meters in length and 6 meters in width, able to transport up to 300 Persian troops at any one trip.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Soon, other states of the empire were constructing their own ships, each incorporating slight local preferences.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships eventually found their way to the Persian Gulf and Persian naval forces laid the foundation for a strong Persian maritime presence there.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Persians also had ships often of a capacity 100 to 200 troops patrolling the empire's various rivers including the Karun, Tigris and Nile in the west, as well as the Indus.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid navy established bases located along the Karun, and in Bahrain, Oman, and Yemen.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian fleet was not only used for peace-keeping purposes along the Karun but also opened the door to trade with India via the Persian Gulf.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius's navy was in many ways a world power at the time, but it would be Artaxerxes II who in the summer of 397 BC would build a formidable navy, as part of a rearmament which would lead to his decisive victory at Knidos in 394 BC, re-establishing Achaemenid power in Ionia.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II would also use his navy to later on quell a rebellion in Egypt.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The construction material of choice was wood, but some armoured Achaemenid ships had metallic blades on the front, often meant to slice enemy ships using the ship's momentum.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Naval ships were also equipped with hooks on the side to grab enemy ships, or to negotiate their position.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships were propelled by sails or manpower.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The ships the Persians created were unique.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] As far as maritime engagement, the ships were equipped with two mangonels that would launch projectiles such as stones, or flammable substances.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Xenophon describes his eyewitness account of a massive military bridge created by joining 37 Persian ships across the Tigris.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persians used each boat's buoyancy to support a connected bridge above which supply could be transferred.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus also gives many accounts of the Persians using ships to build bridges.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Darius I, in an attempt to subdue the Scythian horsemen north of the Black Sea, crossed over at the Bosphorus, using an enormous bridge made by connecting Achaemenid boats, then marched up to the Danube, crossing it by means of a second boat bridge.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The bridge over the Bosphorus essentially connected the nearest tip of Asia to Europe, encompassing at least some 1000 meters of open water if not more.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, a similar boat bridge would be constructed by Xerxes I, in his invasion of Greece.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians failed to capture the Greek city-states completely, the tradition of maritime involvement was carried down by the Persian kings, most notably Artaxerxes II.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Years later, when Alexander invaded Persia and during his advancement into India, he took a page from the Persian art of war, by having Hephaestion and Perdiccas construct a similar boat-bridge at the Indus river in India in the spring of 327 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] They all had the same trilingual inscription (DPh inscription).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Cyrus II and Darius I, and as long as the seat of government was still at Susa in Elam, the language of the chancellery was Elamite.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] This is primarily attested in the Persepolis fortification and treasury tablets that reveal details of the day-to-day functioning of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] In the grand rock-face inscriptions of the kings, the Elamite texts are always accompanied by Akkadian (Babylonian dialect) and Old Persian inscriptions, and it appears that in these cases that the Elamite texts are translations of the Old Persian ones.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] It is then likely that although Elamite was used by the capital government in Susa, it was not a standardized language of government everywhere in the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The use of Elamite is not attested after 458 BC.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Following the conquest of Mesopotamia, the Aramaic language (as used in that territory) was adopted as a "vehicle for written communication between the different regions of the vast empire with its different peoples and languages.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] In 1955, Richard Frye questioned the classification of Imperial Aramaic as an official language, noting that no surviving edict expressly and unambiguously accorded that status to any particular language.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Frye reclassifies Imperial Aramaic as the *lingua franca* of the Achaemenid empire, suggesting that the use of Aramaic language in Achaemenid empire was more widespread than generally thought.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many centuries after the fall of the empire, Aramaic script and—as ideograms—Aramaic vocabulary would survive as the essential characteristics of the Pahlavi writing system.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although Old Persian also appears on some seals and art objects, that language is attested primarily in the Achaemenid inscriptions of Western Iran, suggesting then that Old Persian was the common language of that region.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] When the occasion demanded, Achaemenid administrative correspondence was conducted in Greek, making it a widely used bureaucratic language.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Even though the Achaemenids had extensive contacts with the Greeks and vice versa, and had conquered many of the Greek-speaking areas both in Europe and Asia Minor during different periods of the empire, the native Old Iranian sources provide no indication of Greek linguistic influence.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] However, there is plenty of evidence (in addition to the accounts of Herodotus) that Greeks, apart from being deployed and employed in the core regions of the empire, also evidently lived and worked in the heartland of the Achaemenid Empire, namely Iran.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, Greeks were part of the various ethnicities that constructed Darius' palace in Susa, apart from the Greek inscriptions found nearby there, and one short Persepolis tablet written in Greek.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus mentions that the Persians were invited to great birthday feasts (Herodotus, *Histories* 8), which would be followed by many desserts, a treat which they reproached the Greeks for omitting from their meals.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] He also observed that the Persians drank wine in large quantities and used it even for counsel, deliberating on important affairs when drunk, and deciding the next day, when sober, whether to act on the decision or set it aside.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Religious toleration has been described as a "remarkable feature" of the Achaemenid Empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Hebrew Bible reports that Persian king Cyrus the Great released the Jewish people from the Babylonian captivity in 539–530 BC and permitted them to return to their homeland.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Cyrus the Great assisted in the restoration of the sacred places of various cities, including to rebuild the Israelites’ Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] It was during the Achaemenid period that Zoroastrianism reached southwestern Iran, where it came to be accepted by the rulers and through them became a defining element of Persian culture.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The religion was not only accompanied by a formalization of the concepts and divinities of the traditional Iranian pantheon but also introduced several novel ideas, including that of free will.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Mithra was worshipped in the Empire; his temples and symbols were the most widespread, most people bore names related to him and most festivals were dedicated to him.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] During the reign of Artaxerxes I and Darius II, the Greek historian Herodotus wrote: "[the Persians] have no images of the gods, no temples nor altars, and consider the use of them a sign of folly.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] This comes, I think, from their not believing the gods to have the same nature with men, as the Greeks imagine." He claims the Persians offer sacrifice to: "the sun and moon, to the earth, to fire, to water, and to the winds.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] These are the only gods whose worship has come down to them from ancient times.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] At a later period, they began the worship of Urania, which they borrowed from the Arabians and Assyrians.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Babylonian scholar and priest Berosus records—although writing over seventy years after the reign of Artaxerxes II—that the emperor had been the first to make cult statues of divinities and have them placed in temples in many of the major cities of the empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Berosus also substantiates Herodotus when he says the Persians knew of no images of gods until Artaxerxes II erected those images.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] On the means of sacrifice, Herodotus adds "they raise no altar, light no fire, pour no libations." Herodotus also observed that "no prayer or offering can be made without a magus present".
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The position of women in the Achaemenid Empire varied depending on the culture to which they belonged and therefore differed by region.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The hierarchy of royal women at the Persian court was ranked as follows: the king's mother, then the queen, the king's daughters, the king's concubines, and the other women of the royal palace.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king normally married a female member of the royal family or a Persian noblewoman related to a satrap or another important Persian man; it was permitted for members of the royal family to marry relatives, but there is no evidence for marriage between closer family members than half-siblings.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The king's concubines were often either slaves, sometimes prisoners of war, or foreign princesses, whom the king did not marry because they were foreigners, and whose children did not have the right to inherit the throne.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Greek sources accuse the king of having hundreds of concubines secluded in a harem.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is no archeological evidence supporting the existence of a harem, or the seclusion of women from contact with men, at the Persian court.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The royal women joined the king at breakfast and dinner and accompanied him on his journeys.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] They may have participated in the royal hunt, as well as during the royal banquets.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Herodotus relates how the Persian envoys at the Macedonian court demanded the presence of women during a banquet because it was the custom for women to participate in the banquets in their own country.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The queen may have attended the king's audience, and archeological evidence shows that she gave her own audiences, at least for female supplicants.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal women and noblewomen at court could travel on their own, accompanied by both male and female staff, own and manage their own fortune, land, and business.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Depictions of Persian women show them with long dresses and veils which did not cover their faces or their hair, only flowing down over their neck at the back of the head as an ornament.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic Achaemenid women were given an education in subjects that did not appear compatible with seclusions, such as horsemanship and archery.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women held and managed vast estates and workshops and employed large numbers of servants and professional laborers.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Royal and aristocratic women do not seem to have lived in seclusion from men, since it is known that they appeared in public and traveled with their husbands, participated in hunting and in feasts.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The chief wife of a royal or aristocratic man did not live in seclusion, as it is clearly stated that wives customarily accompanied their husbands at dinner banquets.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] They left the banquet when the "women entertainers" came in and the men began "merrymaking".
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] No woman ever ruled the Achaemenid Empire, as monarch or as regent, but some queen's consorts are known to have had influence over the affairs of state, notably Atossa and Parysatis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] There is not evidence of any women being employed as an official in the administration or within religious service; however, there are plenty of archeological evidence of women being employed as free labourers in Persepolis, where they worked alongside men.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women could be employed as the leaders of their workforce, known by the title *arraššara pašabena*, which were then given a higher salary than the male workers of their workforce.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Female laborers were given less than men.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Qualified workers within the crafts were given equal pay regardless of their sex.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Women are abundant in religious context in the cuneiform sources from late Achaemenid and Hellenistic Babylon.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid architecture included large cities, temples, palaces, and mausolea such as the Tomb of Cyrus the Great.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The quintessential feature of its architecture was its eclectic nature, with elements of Median, Assyrian, and Asiatic Greek all incorporated, yet maintaining a unique Persian identity seen in the finished products.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Its influence pervades the regions ruled by the Achaemenids, from the Mediterranean shores to India, especially with its emphasis on monumental stone-cut design and gardens subdivided by water-courses.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Achaemenid art includes frieze reliefs, metalwork such as the Oxus Treasure, decoration of palaces, glazed brick masonry, fine craftsmanship (masonry, carpentry, etc.), and gardening.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Although the Persians drew artists from all corners of their empire, incorporating their styles and techniques, they did not merely produce a combination of styles, but a synthesis of a new, unique Persian style.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] One of the most remarkable examples of both Achaemenid architecture and art is the grand palace of Persepolis, and its detailed workmanship, coupled with its grand scale.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Many Achaemenid rulers built tombs for themselves.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The most famous, Naqsh-e Rostam, is an ancient necropolis located about 12 km north-west of Persepolis, with the tombs of four of the kings of the dynasty are carved in this mountain: Darius I, Xerxes I, Artaxerxes I and Darius II.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Other kings constructed their own tombs elsewhere.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Artaxerxes II and Artaxerxes III preferred to carve their tombs beside their spring capital Persepolis.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The left tomb belongs to Artaxerxes II and the right tomb belongs to Artaxerxes III, the last Achaemenid king to have a tomb.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The tomb of the founder of the Achaemenid dynasty, Cyrus the Great, was built in Pasargadae (now a world heritage site).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has been referred to as the first “world empire” as it contained in the words of Persian kings “many people and many languages”.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The diverse groups which made up the empire enjoyed a great deal of legal and cultural autonomy.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire has also left a lasting impression on the heritage and cultural identity of Asia and the Middle East, and influenced the development and structure of future empires.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] In fact, the Greeks, and later on the Romans, adopted the best features of the Persian method of governing an empire.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Persian model of governance was particularly formative in the expansion and maintenance of the Abbasid Caliphate, whose rule is widely considered the period of the Islamic Golden Age.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The Achaemenid Empire is noted in Western history as the antagonist of the Greek city-states during the Greco-Persian Wars and for the emancipation of the Jewish exiles in Babylon.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The historical mark of the empire went far beyond its territorial and military influences and included cultural, social, technological and religious influences as well.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] For example, many Athenians adopted Achaemenid customs in their daily lives in a reciprocal cultural exchange, some being employed by or allied to the Persian kings.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The impact of the Edict of Cyrus is mentioned in Judeo-Christian texts, and the empire was instrumental in the spread of Zoroastrianism as far east as China.
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] The empire also set the tone for the politics, heritage and history of Iran (also known as Persia).
[src:achaemenid-empire/achaemenid-empire-p02] Hegel in his work *The Philosophy of History* introduces the Persian Empire as the "first empire that passed away" and its people as the "first historical people" in history.
